{"title_page": "Crakow", "text_new": "{{For|the city|Krak\u00f3w}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n[[File:Arsen 5104 f14 detail2.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Poulaines worn in Burgundy ca. 1470]]\n\n'''Crakows''' or '''crackowes''' were a style of shoes with extremely long toes very popular [[1400\u20131500 in fashion|in the 15th century]]. They were so named because the style was thought to have originated in [[Krak\u00f3w]], then the capital of [[Poland]]. They are also known as '''poulaines''' or '''pikes''',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pratt|first1=Lucy|last2=Woolley|first2=Linda|title=Shoes|date=2008|publisher=V&A Publications|location=London|isbn=978-1-851-77537-8|pages=12\u201313|edition=Pbk.}}</ref> though the term ''poulaine'', as in ''souliers \u00e0 la poulaine'', \"shoes in the Polish fashion\", referred to the long pointed beak of the shoe, not the shoe itself.<ref name=\"Carlson\">{{cite web |last=Carlson |first=I. Marc |date=2001 |url=http://www.personal.utulsa.edu/~marc-carlson/shoe/APP5.HTM |title=Medieval European Long Toed Shoes |website=Footwear of The Middle Ages}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nLong-toed shoes had been popular in Europe at different times, first appearing in the archaeological record in the 12th century and falling in and out of fashion periodically. They reached their most exaggerated form in the third quarter of the 15th century before falling out of fashion in the 1480s.<ref name=\"stt\">{{cite book |last1=Goubitz |first1=Olaf |last2=van Driel-Murray |first2=Carol |last3=Groenman-Van Waateringe |first3=Willy |date=2001 |title=Stepping Through Time: Archaeological Footwear from Prehistoric Times until 1800 |location=Zwolle [Netherlands] |publisher=Stichting Promotie Archeologie |isbn= 9789080104464}}</ref><ref name=\"s+p\">{{cite book |last1=Grew |first1=Francis |last2=de Neergaard |first2=Margrethe |date=1988 |title=Shoes and Pattens |series=Medieval Finds from Excavations in London |volume=2 |location=Woodbridge |publisher=Boydell Press |isbn=9780851158389 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KpVth0J2IncC&pg=PA88#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>{{rp|88\u20139}}\n\nThe arrival of this fashion in England is traditionally associated with the marriage of [[Richard II]] and [[Anne of Bohemia]] in 1382. An anonymous 'monk of Evesham' recorded in 1394: \"With this queen there came from Bohemia into England those accursed vices (English ''Cracowys'' or ''Pykys'') half a yard in length, thus it was necessary for them to be tied to the shin with chains of silver before they could walk with them.\"\n\nHowever, there are indications they were worn as early as the 1360s. The author of the ''Eulogium Historiarum'' describes men of this period as wearing \"points on their shoes as long as your finger that are called crakowes; more suitable as claws... for demons than as ornaments for men.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chambers|first1=Mark|last2=Sylvester|first2=Louise|editor1-last=Hamling|editor1-first=Tara|editor2-last=Richardson|editor2-first=Catherine|title=Everyday Objects: Medieval and Early Modern Material Culture and its Meanings|chapter=Lexicological Confusion and Medieval Clothing Culture: Redressing Medieval Dress with the Lexis of Cloth and Clothing in Britain Project|date=2010|publisher=Ashgate Pub.|location=Farnham, Surrey, England|isbn=0754666379|pages=71\u201384|edition=Repr.}}</ref>\n\n14th-century poulaine-toed shoes found in London were found only in men's sizes,{{r|s+p|pp=88\u20139}} but 15th century art shows them being worn by both men and women, with the toes of men's shoes being the most extravagantly long. They were a controversial fashion and faced criticism from several quarters. In 1368, [[Charles V of France]] issued an edict banning their construction and use in Paris. An English poem from 1388 complained that men were unable to kneel in prayer because their toes were too long.<ref name=\"scott\">{{cite book|last1=Scott|first1=Margaret|title=Medieval Clothing and Costumes: Displaying Wealth and Class in Medieval Times|date=2004|publisher=Rosen Central|location=New York|isbn=082393991X|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/medievalclothing0000scot}}</ref> \n\nIn 1463, [[Edward IV]] passed a [[sumptuary law]] restricting anyone \"under the state of a Lord, Esquire, [or] Gentleman\" from wearing poulaines over the length of two inches. In 1465, they were banned in England altogether, so that all [[cordwainer]]s and [[Cobbling|cobbler]]s within the [[City of London]] were prohibited from making shoes with pikes more than two inches long.{{r|s+p|p=117}}\n\nThe poulaine inspired later footwear fashions, such as the 1950s [[Winklepicker]] boots.\n\n==Features==\n===Stuffing===\nPoulaine toes were packed with stuffing to provide rigidity and help them hold their shape. Surviving examples from medieval London have the points stuffed with [[moss]].<ref name=\"stt\" /> An Italian chronicler noted in 1388 that they were also sometimes stuffed with horsehair.<ref name=\"scott\"/>\n\n===Tying up the toes===\nAlthough there is no archaeological or medieval iconographic evidence to support the idea that the toes were ever tied up to the leg,<ref name=\"Carlson\" /> as noted earlier, there is direct literary evidence dating from 1394 which states that this was the practice at the time these shoes were introduced into England.  Additionally, the practice is mentioned by the antiquarian [[John Stow]] in his 1698 publication ''A Survey of London'', where he wrote:\n{{cquote | \"In Distar Lane, on the north side thereof, is the [[shoemaking|Cordwainer's]] Hall, which company were made a brotherhood or fraternity in the eleventh of Henry IV. Of these cordwainers, I read, that since the fifth of [[Richard II of England|Richard II]] (when he took to wife [[Anne of Bohemia|Anne]], daughter to [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Wenceslaus]] [sic], King of [[Bohemia]]), by her example the English people had used piked shoes, tied to their knees with silken laces, or chains of silver or gilt, wherefore in the fourth of Edward IV it was ordained and proclaimed that beaks of [[shoe|shoon]] and boots should not pass the length of two inches, upon pain of cursing by the clergy, and by Parliament to pay twenty shillings for every pair. And every cordwainer that shod any man or woman on the Sunday, to pay thirty shillings\".<ref>{{cite book |first=John |last=Stow |authorlink=John Stow |chapter=Bredstreete warde |title=A Survey of London. Reprinted From the Text of 1603 |editor-first=C. L. |editor-last=Kingsford |location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon |date=1908 |pages=344-352 |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/no-series/survey-of-london-stow/1603/pp344-352}}</ref>}}\n\nHowever, given that John Stow was writing over 100 years after the shoes fell out of fashion, and the lack of rigorous historical research in the writings of the time, he cannot be considered a reliable source. His record of Act 4 of Edward IV is exaggerated - the actual act does mention restrictions in length, but not monetary penalties, parliament or clergy:\n{{cquote | Nulle persone Cordewaner ou Cobeler .. face.. ascuns soler galoges ou husend oveqe ascun pike ou poleine qe passera la longuer ou mesure de deux poutz.<ref name=\"Carlson\" />}}\n\n[[File:2008-08 archeon schnabelschuh.JPG|thumb|Poulaine at the shoemaker of [[Archeon, Netherlands|Archeon]]]]\n\n===Poulaines as overshoes===\nOvershoes made from leather or cork, called [[pattens]], were frequently worn with late medieval shoes both indoors and outdoors. The shape of pattens reflected the style of shoes in different periods, and pattens during the period where poulaine toes were fashionable have matching long toes. These pattens would have supported the toe of the shoes if required.\n\n===Toe length===\nArchaeological evidence in the form of surviving shoe soles shows that the length of the point beyond the toes of the foot was rarely, if ever, more than 50% of the length of the foot.<ref name=\"stt\" />{{r|s+p|pp=88\u20139}}This is consistent with depictions of highly fashionable European men from the third quarter of the 15th century when poulaine toes were at the height of their popularity.\n\n[[File:Sempach Schilling.jpg|thumb|300px|Depiction of the [[Battle of Sempach]] in the [[Luzerner Schilling]], showing a large pile of shoe-tips on a hill in the upper-left of the illustration (1513)]]\nAs with many items of high fashion the most extreme examples were worn by the upper classes. In periods when poulaine toes were popular most shoes were somewhat pointed, even those used during warfare.  There is clear evidence from the [[Battle of Sempach]] that in certain periods soldiers on campaign wore shoes with toes so long as to interfere with the wearer's ability to run.  In that battle, it became necessary for the knights of [[Leopold III, Duke of Austria]] to dismount and fight on foot, and because they did not have time to prepare for the engagement, they were forced to cut off the tips of their poulaines. The Swiss chroniclers report how a huge pile of these shoe-tips was found in a heap after the battle, and they are also depicted in the background of the battle scene in the [[Lucerne Chronicle]] of 1513.\n\n[[File:HJRK A 62 - Armoured shoes of Maximilian I, 1485.jpg|thumb|left|Sabatons of [[Emperor Maximilian I]], c. 1485]]\nA surviving pair of [[sabatons]] belonging to Emperor Maximilian have extremely long poulaines, but they were used only on horseback and in this case the long points were detachable from the sabatons for foot combat. The catches can be seen over the area of the big toe.\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Poulaine}}\n*[[Winklepicker|Pointed shoe]]\n*[[Venetian-style shoe]]\n*[[Pigache]]\n*[[Winklepicker]]\n*[[Duckbill shoe]] (contrasting suceeding style)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Footwear}}\n{{Historical clothing}}\n\n[[Category:Shoes]]\n[[Category:Historical footwear]]\n[[Category:Polish clothing]]\n[[Category:Medieval European costume]]\n[[Category:15th century in Europe]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the city|Krak\u00f3w}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n[[File:Arsen 5104 f14 detail2.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Poulaines worn in Burgundy ca. 1470]]\n\n'''Crakows''' or '''crackowes''' were a style of shoes with extremely long toes very popular [[1400\u20131500 in fashion|in the 15th century]]. They were so named because the style was thought to have originated in [[Krak\u00f3w]], then the capital of [[Poland]]. They are also known as '''poulaines''' or '''pikes''',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pratt|first1=Lucy|last2=Woolley|first2=Linda|title=Shoes|date=2008|publisher=V&A Publications|location=London|isbn=978-1-851-77537-8|pages=12\u201313|edition=Pbk.}}</ref> though the term ''poulaine'', as in ''souliers \u00e0 la poulaine'', \"shoes in the Polish fashion\", referred to the long pointed beak of the shoe, not the shoe itself.<ref name=\"Carlson\">{{cite web |last=Carlson |first=I. Marc |date=2001 |url=http://www.personal.utulsa.edu/~marc-carlson/shoe/APP5.HTM |title=Medieval European Long Toed Shoes |website=Footwear of The Middle Ages}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nLong-toed shoes had been popular in Europe at different times, first appearing in the archaeological record in the 12th century and falling in and out of fashion periodically. They reached their most exaggerated form in the third quarter of the 15th century before falling out of fashion in the 1480s.<ref name=\"stt\">{{cite book |last1=Goubitz |first1=Olaf |last2=van Driel-Murray |first2=Carol |last3=Groenman-Van Waateringe |first3=Willy |date=2001 |title=Stepping Through Time: Archaeological Footwear from Prehistoric Times until 1800 |location=Zwolle [Netherlands] |publisher=Stichting Promotie Archeologie |isbn= 9789080104464}}</ref><ref name=\"s+p\">{{cite book |last1=Grew |first1=Francis |last2=de Neergaard |first2=Margrethe |date=1988 |title=Shoes and Pattens |series=Medieval Finds from Excavations in London |volume=2 |location=Woodbridge |publisher=Boydell Press |isbn=9780851158389 |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KpVth0J2IncC&pg=PA88#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>{{rp|88\u20139}}\n\nThe arrival of this fashion in England is traditionally associated with the marriage of [[Richard II]] and [[Anne of Bohemia]] in 1382. An anonymous 'monk of Evesham' recorded in 1394: \"With this queen there came from Bohemia into England those accursed vices (English ''Cracowys'' or ''Pykys'') half a yard in length, thus it was necessary for them to be tied to the shin with chains of silver before they could walk with them.\"\n\nHowever, there are indications they were worn as early as the 1360s. The author of the ''Eulogium Historiarum'' describes men of this period as wearing \"points on their shoes as long as your finger that are called crakowes; more suitable as claws... for demons than as ornaments for men.\"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Chambers|first1=Mark|last2=Sylvester|first2=Louise|editor1-last=Hamling|editor1-first=Tara|editor2-last=Richardson|editor2-first=Catherine|title=Everyday Objects: Medieval and Early Modern Material Culture and its Meanings|chapter=Lexicological Confusion and Medieval Clothing Culture: Redressing Medieval Dress with the Lexis of Cloth and Clothing in Britain Project|date=2010|publisher=Ashgate Pub.|location=Farnham, Surrey, England|isbn=0754666379|pages=71\u201384|edition=Repr.}}</ref>\n\n14th-century poulaine-toed shoes found in London were found only in men's sizes,{{r|s+p|pp=88\u20139}} but 15th century art shows them being worn by both men and women, with the toes of men's shoes being the most extravagantly long. They were a controversial fashion and faced criticism from several quarters. In 1368, [[Charles V of France]] issued an edict banning their construction and use in Paris. An English poem from 1388 complained that men were unable to kneel in prayer because their toes were too long.<ref name=\"scott\">{{cite book|last1=Scott|first1=Margaret|title=Medieval Clothing and Costumes: Displaying Wealth and Class in Medieval Times|date=2004|publisher=Rosen Central|location=New York|isbn=082393991X|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/medievalclothing0000scot}}</ref> \n\nIn 1463, [[Edward IV]] passed a [[sumptuary law]] restricting anyone \"under the state of a Lord, Esquire, [or] Gentleman\" from wearing poulaines over the length of two inches. In 1465, they were banned in England altogether, so that all [[cordwainer]]s and [[Cobbling|cobbler]]s within the [[City of London]] were prohibited from making shoes with pikes more than two inches long.{{r|s+p|p=117}}\n\nThe poulaine inspired later footwear fashions, such as the 1950s [[Winklepicker]] boots.\n\n==Features==\n===Stuffing===\nPoulaine toes were packed with stuffing to provide rigidity and help them hold their shape. Surviving examples from medieval London have the points stuffed with [[moss]].<ref name=\"stt\" /> An Italian chronicler noted in 1388 that they were also sometimes stuffed with horsehair.<ref name=\"scott\"/>\n\n===Tying up the toes===\nAlthough there is no archaeological or medieval iconographic evidence to support the idea that the toes were ever tied up to the leg,<ref name=\"Carlson\" /> as noted earlier, there is direct literary evidence dating from 1394 which states that this was the practice at the time these shoes were introduced into England.  Additionally, the practice is mentioned by the antiquarian [[John Stow]] in his 1698 publication ''A Survey of London'', where he wrote:\n{{cquote | \"In Distar Lane, on the north side thereof, is the [[shoemaking|Cordwainer's]] Hall, which company were made a brotherhood or fraternity in the eleventh of Henry IV. Of these cordwainers, I read, that since the fifth of [[Richard II of England|Richard II]] (when he took to wife [[Anne of Bohemia|Anne]], daughter to [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Wenceslaus]] [sic], King of [[Bohemia]]), by her example the English people had used piked shoes, tied to their knees with silken laces, or chains of silver or gilt, wherefore in the fourth of Edward IV it was ordained and proclaimed that beaks of [[shoe|shoon]] and boots should not pass the length of two inches, upon pain of cursing by the clergy, and by Parliament to pay twenty shillings for every pair. And every cordwainer that shod any man or woman on the Sunday, to pay thirty shillings\".<ref>{{cite book |first=John |last=Stow |authorlink=John Stow |chapter=Bredstreete warde |title=A Survey of London. Reprinted From the Text of 1603 |editor-first=C. L. |editor-last=Kingsford |location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon |date=1908 |pages=344-352 |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/no-series/survey-of-london-stow/1603/pp344-352}}</ref>}}\n\nHowever, given that John Stow was writing over 100 years after the shoes fell out of fashion, and the lack of rigorous historical research in the writings of the time, he cannot be considered a reliable source. His record of Act 4 of Edward IV is exaggerated - the actual act does mention restrictions in length, but not monetary penalties, parliament or clergy:\n{{cquote | Nulle persone Cordewaner ou Cobeler .. face.. ascuns soler galoges ou husend oveqe ascun pike ou poleine qe passera la longuer ou mesure de deux poutz.<ref name=\"Carlson\" />}}\n\n[[File:2008-08 archeon schnabelschuh.JPG|thumb|Poulaine at the shoemaker of [[Archeon, Netherlands|Archeon]]]]\n\n===Poulaines as overshoes===\nOvershoes made from leather or cork, called [[pattens]], were frequently worn with late medieval shoes both indoors and outdoors. The shape of pattens reflected the style of shoes in different periods, and pattens during the period where poulaine toes were fashionable have matching long toes. These pattens would have supported the toe of the shoes if required.\n\n===Toe length===\nArchaeological evidence in the form of surviving shoe soles shows that the length of the point beyond the toes of the foot was rarely, if ever, more than 50% of the length of the foot.<ref name=\"stt\" />{{r|s+p|pp=88\u20139}}This is consistent with depictions of highly fashionable European men from the third quarter of the 15th century when poulaine toes were at the height of their popularity.\n\n[[File:Sempach Schilling.jpg|thumb|300px|Depiction of the [[Battle of Sempach]] in the [[Luzerner Schilling]], showing a large pile of shoe-tips on a hill in the upper-left of the illustration (1513)]]\nAs with many items of high fashion the most extreme examples were worn by the upper classes. In periods when poulaine toes were popular most shoes were somewhat pointed, even those used during warfare.  There is clear evidence from the [[Battle of Sempach]] that in certain periods soldiers on campaign wore shoes with toes so long as to interfere with the wearer's ability to run.  In that battle, it became necessary for the knights of [[Leopold III, Duke of Austria]] to dismount and fight on foot, and because they did not have time to prepare for the engagement, they were forced to cut off the tips of their poulaines. The Swiss chroniclers report how a huge pile of these shoe-tips was found in a heap after the battle, and they are also depicted in the background of the battle scene in the [[Lucerne Chronicle]] of 1513.\n\n[[File:HJRK A 62 - Armoured shoes of Maximilian I, 1485.jpg|thumb|left|Sabatons of [[Emperor Maximilian I]], c. 1485]]\nA surviving pair of [[sabatons]] belonging to Emperor Maximilian have extremely long poulaines, but they were used only on horseback and in this case the long points were detachable from the sabatons for foot combat. The catches can be seen over the area of the big toe.\n\n==See also==\n{{commons category|Poulaine}}\n*[[Winklepicker|Pointed shoe]]\n*[[Venetian-style shoe]]\n*[[Pigache]]\n*[[Winklepicker]]\n*[[Duckbill shoe]] (contrasting suceeding style)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{Footwear}}\n{{Historical clothing}}\n\n[[Category:Shoes]]\n[[Category:Historical footwear]]\n[[Category:Polish clothing]]\n[[Category:Medieval costume]]\n[[Category:15th century in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:Medieval costumetoCategory:Medieval European costumeusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crakow"}
{"title_page": "Miner's apron", "text_new": "[[File:Bergmannskostuem 13 Jh mit Arschleder und Bergeisen.jpg|thumb|150px|Miner's costume showing the miner's apron or ''Bergleder'']]\n[[File:Bergmann der auf dem Leder einfaert.png|thumb|upright|right|Miner entering a mine sitting on his apron (by Georg Agricola)]]\n[[File:Annaberger-Bergaltar2.jpg|thumb|Depiction of miners with aprons at the Annaberg Miners' Altar (1521)]]\n\nThe '''miner's apron''' ({{lang-de|Arschleder}}, ''Bergleder'' or ''Fahrleder'') is part of the clothing worn, especially historically,  by [[miner]]s in the [[mining]] industries of German-speaking Europe. Variously called in English a miner's apron,<ref name=\"Bucksch\"/> a miner's after-apron,<ref>Ebers, John (1796). ''The New and Complete Dictionary of the German and English Languages'', Vol. 1, Breitkopf & Hertel, Leipzig, 1796.</ref><ref>Ebers, John (1802). ''A New Hand-Dictionary of the German Language, For Englishmen and of the English Language for the Germans'', Vol. 2, Halle, 1802, p. 230.</ref> breech leather<ref name=\"Bucksch\">Bucksch, Herbert (1997). ''Dictionary Geotechnical Engineering'', Vol. 2, Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg, New York, p. 77, {{ISBN|3-540-58163-4}}.</ref><ref>K\u00fcttner, C.G. and Nicholson, W. (1805). ''New and Complete Dictionary of the German Language for Englishmen'', Vol. 1, Schwickertsche Verlage, Leipzig, p. 131.</ref><ref>Ciba-Geigy review, Volume 12, Issues 133-141, p. 154, 1959.</ref> or miner's leather apron,<ref>Pohs, Henry A. (1995). ''The miner's flame light book'', Flame Pub. Co., pp. 107 and 119.</ref> it was a leather apron that served to keep the seat of the trousers from wearing out when working or moving around the mine (''Fahrung'') as well as keeping out the cold and moisture when sitting. It also provided protection especially when entering inclined [[shaft mining|mineshaft]]s. Another advantage was that it stabilised the internal organs from mechanical shock and vibration by acting as a sort of [[kidney belt]]. The miner's apron was a triangular or, more rarely, semi-circular piece of leather and was supported by the [[belt (clothing)|body belt]]. In Germany the design of the modern miner's apron is governed by DIN standard 23307 ''Ges\u00e4\u00dfleder f\u00fcr den Bergbau (Arschleder)''.\n\n== History ==\nThe mining apron was introduced to German mining regions in the 15th century from the [[Slovakia]]n mining area around [[Bansk\u00e1 \u0160tiavnica|Schemnitz]] (Bansk\u00e1 \u0160tiavnica). Early illustrations of it are found on the title page of the \"Little Mining Book\" (''Bergb\u00fcchlein'') by [[Ulrich R\u00fclein von Calw]] (1505) and on the [[St. Anne's Church, Annaberg-Buchholz#Miners' altar|miner's altar of St. Anne's Church in Annaberg]] (1521). [[Georgius Agricola]] wrote in this book ''[[De re metallica]]'' (1556):{{quotation|So sat the miners on their aprons, which were tied around their loins, and hung down behind them. <br />\n(''So sitzend die Bergh\u00e4wer auf ihr Arsleder, das um die Lenden gebunden, dahinter herabhanget.'')}}\n\nPermission to wear the miner's apron was only granted to miners and mining officials. Analogous to the [[hammer and chisel]], it represented a unifying symbol of miners' status. Later, it was also worn outside work in decorative styles as part of the [[miner's uniform]] (''Berghabit'') or parade uniform (''Paradeuniform'') for [[miners' parade]]s (''Bergparaden''). In events connected with mining [[customs]], this device is also used for the so-called \"leather jump\" (''Ledersprung''), a form of miners' initiation ceremony in Austria.\n\n== Folk art and music ==\nThe apron of the miner is incorporated into the design of the wooden [[smoking figurine]]s and [[nutcracker]]s made in the [[Ore Mountains]]. It has also made its way into the mining songs. Thus we read in the last stanza of the version of the mine foremen's song (''Steigerlied'') sung in the [[Ruhr]] and [[Saarland|Saar]]: {{quotation|The mining folk are terribly good folk<br />because they wear the leather over their bum at night<br />because they wear the leather over their bum at night<br />and drink ''[[schnaps]]'', and drink ''schnaps''.<br />\n''Die Bergleut sein kreuzbrave Leut\u2019<br />denn sie tragen das Leder vor dem Arsch bei der Nacht<br />denn sie tragen das Leder vor dem Arsch bei der Nacht<br />und saufen Schnaps, und saufen Schnaps.''}}\n\n== Similar uses ==\nIn [[Kite|stunt kite flying]] the leather apron is used especially in [[power kiting]] or [[kite surfing]] using powered kites. The pilot sits on a leather apron that protects the seat of his trousers and is hauled by the kite over rough ground (e.g., pastureland).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Miner's habit]]\n* [[Miner's cap]]\n* [[Mooskappe]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* Walter Schellhas: ''Das Arschleder des Bergmanns'', in: [[S\u00e4chsische Heimatbl\u00e4tter]] Heft 6/1987, pp.&nbsp;280\u2013281\n* Carl Friedrich Richter: ''Neuestes Berg-und H\u00fctten-Lexikon.'' 1st Volume, Kleefeldsche Buchhandlung, Leipzig, 1805\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.jugendheim-gersbach.de/Schwazer-Bergbuch-Vorderoesterreich-Tirol-Bergknappe-Arschleder-Hunt.jpg Illustration of a miner with miner's apron (triangular type)]\n\n[[Category:History of mining]]\n[[Category:Mining culture and traditions]]\n[[Category:Medieval European costume]]\n[[Category:Protective gear]]\n[[Category:Miners' clothing]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Bergmannskostuem 13 Jh mit Arschleder und Bergeisen.jpg|thumb|150px|Miner's costume showing the miner's apron or ''Bergleder'']]\n[[File:Bergmann der auf dem Leder einfaert.png|thumb|upright|right|Miner entering a mine sitting on his apron (by Georg Agricola)]]\n[[File:Annaberger-Bergaltar2.jpg|thumb|Depiction of miners with aprons at the Annaberg Miners' Altar (1521)]]\n\nThe '''miner's apron''' ({{lang-de|Arschleder}}, ''Bergleder'' or ''Fahrleder'') is part of the clothing worn, especially historically,  by [[miner]]s in the [[mining]] industries of German-speaking Europe. Variously called in English a miner's apron,<ref name=\"Bucksch\"/> a miner's after-apron,<ref>Ebers, John (1796). ''The New and Complete Dictionary of the German and English Languages'', Vol. 1, Breitkopf & Hertel, Leipzig, 1796.</ref><ref>Ebers, John (1802). ''A New Hand-Dictionary of the German Language, For Englishmen and of the English Language for the Germans'', Vol. 2, Halle, 1802, p. 230.</ref> breech leather<ref name=\"Bucksch\">Bucksch, Herbert (1997). ''Dictionary Geotechnical Engineering'', Vol. 2, Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg, New York, p. 77, {{ISBN|3-540-58163-4}}.</ref><ref>K\u00fcttner, C.G. and Nicholson, W. (1805). ''New and Complete Dictionary of the German Language for Englishmen'', Vol. 1, Schwickertsche Verlage, Leipzig, p. 131.</ref><ref>Ciba-Geigy review, Volume 12, Issues 133-141, p. 154, 1959.</ref> or miner's leather apron,<ref>Pohs, Henry A. (1995). ''The miner's flame light book'', Flame Pub. Co., pp. 107 and 119.</ref> it was a leather apron that served to keep the seat of the trousers from wearing out when working or moving around the mine (''Fahrung'') as well as keeping out the cold and moisture when sitting. It also provided protection especially when entering inclined [[shaft mining|mineshaft]]s. Another advantage was that it stabilised the internal organs from mechanical shock and vibration by acting as a sort of [[kidney belt]]. The miner's apron was a triangular or, more rarely, semi-circular piece of leather and was supported by the [[belt (clothing)|body belt]]. In Germany the design of the modern miner's apron is governed by DIN standard 23307 ''Ges\u00e4\u00dfleder f\u00fcr den Bergbau (Arschleder)''.\n\n== History ==\nThe mining apron was introduced to German mining regions in the 15th century from the [[Slovakia]]n mining area around [[Bansk\u00e1 \u0160tiavnica|Schemnitz]] (Bansk\u00e1 \u0160tiavnica). Early illustrations of it are found on the title page of the \"Little Mining Book\" (''Bergb\u00fcchlein'') by [[Ulrich R\u00fclein von Calw]] (1505) and on the [[St. Anne's Church, Annaberg-Buchholz#Miners' altar|miner's altar of St. Anne's Church in Annaberg]] (1521). [[Georgius Agricola]] wrote in this book ''[[De re metallica]]'' (1556):{{quotation|So sat the miners on their aprons, which were tied around their loins, and hung down behind them. <br />\n(''So sitzend die Bergh\u00e4wer auf ihr Arsleder, das um die Lenden gebunden, dahinter herabhanget.'')}}\n\nPermission to wear the miner's apron was only granted to miners and mining officials. Analogous to the [[hammer and chisel]], it represented a unifying symbol of miners' status. Later, it was also worn outside work in decorative styles as part of the [[miner's uniform]] (''Berghabit'') or parade uniform (''Paradeuniform'') for [[miners' parade]]s (''Bergparaden''). In events connected with mining [[customs]], this device is also used for the so-called \"leather jump\" (''Ledersprung''), a form of miners' initiation ceremony in Austria.\n\n== Folk art and music ==\nThe apron of the miner is incorporated into the design of the wooden [[smoking figurine]]s and [[nutcracker]]s made in the [[Ore Mountains]]. It has also made its way into the mining songs. Thus we read in the last stanza of the version of the mine foremen's song (''Steigerlied'') sung in the [[Ruhr]] and [[Saarland|Saar]]: {{quotation|The mining folk are terribly good folk<br />because they wear the leather over their bum at night<br />because they wear the leather over their bum at night<br />and drink ''[[schnaps]]'', and drink ''schnaps''.<br />\n''Die Bergleut sein kreuzbrave Leut\u2019<br />denn sie tragen das Leder vor dem Arsch bei der Nacht<br />denn sie tragen das Leder vor dem Arsch bei der Nacht<br />und saufen Schnaps, und saufen Schnaps.''}}\n\n== Similar uses ==\nIn [[Kite|stunt kite flying]] the leather apron is used especially in [[power kiting]] or [[kite surfing]] using powered kites. The pilot sits on a leather apron that protects the seat of his trousers and is hauled by the kite over rough ground (e.g., pastureland).\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Miner's habit]]\n* [[Miner's cap]]\n* [[Mooskappe]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Literature ==\n* Walter Schellhas: ''Das Arschleder des Bergmanns'', in: [[S\u00e4chsische Heimatbl\u00e4tter]] Heft 6/1987, pp.&nbsp;280\u2013281\n* Carl Friedrich Richter: ''Neuestes Berg-und H\u00fctten-Lexikon.'' 1st Volume, Kleefeldsche Buchhandlung, Leipzig, 1805\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.jugendheim-gersbach.de/Schwazer-Bergbuch-Vorderoesterreich-Tirol-Bergknappe-Arschleder-Hunt.jpg Illustration of a miner with miner's apron (triangular type)]\n\n[[Category:History of mining]]\n[[Category:Mining culture and traditions]]\n[[Category:Medieval costume]]\n[[Category:Protective gear]]\n[[Category:Miners' clothing]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:Medieval costumetoCategory:Medieval European costumeusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miner%27s_apron"}
{"title_page": "Chopine", "text_new": "{{about|footwear|the liquid measure|Units of measurement in France before the French Revolution#Volume - Liquid measures}}\n[[File:Shoemuseum Lausanne-IMG 7291.JPG|thumb|Reconstruction of a 16th-century Venetian chopine. On display at the Shoe Museum in Lausanne.]]\n[[File:Chopine (PSF).jpg|thumb|Line art drawing of a chopine.]]\n\nA '''chopine''' is a type of women's [[platform shoe]] that was popular in the 15th, 16th and 17th centuries. Chopines were originally used as a [[Patten (shoe)|patten]], [[clog (shoe)|clog]], or [[overshoe]] to protect the shoes and dress from mud and street soil.  \n\nChopines were popularly worn in [[Venice]] by both [[courtesan]]s and patrician women from c. 1400 to 1700. Besides their practical uses, the height of the chopine became a symbolic reference to the cultural and social standing of the wearer; the higher the chopine, the higher the status of the wearer.<ref>Coryat Thomas, ''Crudities'' (London, 1611) ed. 1905, p. 400.</ref> High chopines allowed a woman to tower over others. During the [[Renaissance]], chopines became an article of women's [[fashion]] and were made increasingly taller; some extant examples are over 20&nbsp;inches (50&nbsp;cm) high.<ref>The tallest extant chopines are in the Museo Correr in Venice, Italy.</ref> In 1430, the height of chopines was [[High heel policy|limited by Venetian law]] to three inches, but this regulation was widely ignored.<ref name=\"DeMello2009\">{{cite book |author=Margo DeMello |title=Feet and Footwear: A Cultural Encyclopedia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5QdKSxajwP0C&pg=PA311 |year=2009 |publisher=Greenwood Press/ABC-CLIO |isbn=978-0-313-35714-5 |page=311}}</ref> [[Shakespeare]] joked about the extreme height of the chopines in style in his day by using the word ''altitude'' (''[[Hamlet]]'' 2.2, the prince greets one of the visiting players&nbsp;\u2013 the adolescent boy who would have played the female parts in the all-male troupe&nbsp;\u2013 by noting how much \"nearer to heaven\" the lad had grown since he last saw him \"by the altitude of a chopine\").\n\nSurviving chopines are typically made of [[wood]] or [[Cork (material)|cork]], and those in the Spanish style were sometimes banded about with [[metal]]. Extant pieces are covered with [[leather]], brocades, or jewel-embroidered [[velvet]]. Often, the fabric of the chopine matched the dress or the shoe, but not always. However, despite being highly decorated, chopines were often hidden under the wearer's skirt and were hidden from any critical observation. Although due to the design of the shoes, they caused the wearer to have a very \"comical walk\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to some scholars, chopines caused an unstable and inelegant gait. Noblewomen wearing them were generally accompanied by two servants in order to walk around safely, by supporting themselves on the servants' shoulders.<ref name=\":0\">Bossan, Marie-Jos\u00e8phe. \"The Renaissance\". ''The Art of the Shoe''. Trans. Rebecca Brimacombe. New York: Parkstone, 2012. p. 35. via Google Books. Parkstone International, 08 May 2012. Web. 02 May 2014. <<nowiki>https://books.google.com/books?id=2Ifj9h4Z4YQC&pg=PA35&dq=chopines</nowiki> shoes&hl=en&sa=X&ei=SDhkU_q3H5DZoAS4hoKQAw&ved=0CEYQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=chopines shoes&f=false>.</ref> Other scholars have argued that with practice a woman could walk and even dance gracefully.<ref>Barbara Ravelhofer, ''The Early Stuart Masque: Dance, Costume, and Music'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2006), p. 113, fn 47.</ref> In his dancing manual ''Nobilit\u00e0 di dame'' (1600), the Italian dancing master [[Fabritio Caroso]] writes that with care a woman practiced in wearing her chopines could move \u201cwith grace, seemliness, and beauty\u201d and even \"dance flourishes and [[galliard]] variations\".<ref>[[Fabritio Caroso]], ''Nobilit\u00e0 di dame'' (Venice, 1600), translated as ''Courtly Dance of the Renaissance: Nobilit\u00e0 di dame'', ed. and trans. Julia Sutton and F. Marian Walker (New York, 1995), p. 141.</ref> Chopines were usually put on with the help of two servants.\n\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:MFA chopine.jpg]] -->\nIn the 15th century, chopines were also the style in [[Spain]]. Their popularity in Spain was so great that the larger part of the nation's cork supplies went towards production of the shoes. Some argue{{who|date=April 2015}} that the style originated in Spain, as there are many extant examples and a great amount of pictorial and written reference going back to the 14th century.<ref>[[Anderson, Ruth Matilda]]. ''Hispanic costume, 1480-1530.''</ref> Chopines of the Spanish style were more often conical and symmetric, while their Venetian counterparts are much more artistically carved. That is not to say, however, that Spanish chopines were not adorned; on the contrary, there is evidence of jeweling, gilt lettering along the surround (the material covering the cork or wooden base), tooling, and embroidery on Spanish chopines. \n\nThere are a great many cognates of the word chopine (chapiney, choppins, etc.). However, neither the word chopine nor any word similar to it (chioppino, cioppino, etc.) appears in Florio's dictionaries of either 1598 or 1611. The Italian word, instead, seems to be \"zoccoli\", which likely comes from the Italian word \"zocco,\" meaning a stump or a block of wood. Florio does, however, use the word \"chopinos\" in his English definition of zoccoli.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Geta (footwear)]]\n* [[Pint#Other pints|Chopine, volume]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wiktionary}}\n{{Commonscat|Chopines}}\n* http://www.aands.org/raisedheels\n* http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/~ebernhar/index.shtml\n* http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/ho/08/eustn/hod_1973.114.4a,b.htm\n\n{{footwear}}\n{{Historical clothing}}\n\n[[Category:Historical footwear]]\n[[Category:Medieval European costume]]\n[[Category:Shoes]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|footwear|the liquid measure|Units of measurement in France before the French Revolution#Volume - Liquid measures}}\n[[File:Shoemuseum Lausanne-IMG 7291.JPG|thumb|Reconstruction of a 16th-century Venetian chopine. On display at the Shoe Museum in Lausanne.]]\n[[File:Chopine (PSF).jpg|thumb|Line art drawing of a chopine.]]\n\nA '''chopine''' is a type of women's [[platform shoe]] that was popular in the 15th, 16th and 17th centuries. Chopines were originally used as a [[Patten (shoe)|patten]], [[clog (shoe)|clog]], or [[overshoe]] to protect the shoes and dress from mud and street soil.  \n\nChopines were popularly worn in [[Venice]] by both [[courtesan]]s and patrician women from c. 1400 to 1700. Besides their practical uses, the height of the chopine became a symbolic reference to the cultural and social standing of the wearer; the higher the chopine, the higher the status of the wearer.<ref>Coryat Thomas, ''Crudities'' (London, 1611) ed. 1905, p. 400.</ref> High chopines allowed a woman to tower over others. During the [[Renaissance]], chopines became an article of women's [[fashion]] and were made increasingly taller; some extant examples are over 20&nbsp;inches (50&nbsp;cm) high.<ref>The tallest extant chopines are in the Museo Correr in Venice, Italy.</ref> In 1430, the height of chopines was [[High heel policy|limited by Venetian law]] to three inches, but this regulation was widely ignored.<ref name=\"DeMello2009\">{{cite book |author=Margo DeMello |title=Feet and Footwear: A Cultural Encyclopedia |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5QdKSxajwP0C&pg=PA311 |year=2009 |publisher=Greenwood Press/ABC-CLIO |isbn=978-0-313-35714-5 |page=311}}</ref> [[Shakespeare]] joked about the extreme height of the chopines in style in his day by using the word ''altitude'' (''[[Hamlet]]'' 2.2, the prince greets one of the visiting players&nbsp;\u2013 the adolescent boy who would have played the female parts in the all-male troupe&nbsp;\u2013 by noting how much \"nearer to heaven\" the lad had grown since he last saw him \"by the altitude of a chopine\").\n\nSurviving chopines are typically made of [[wood]] or [[Cork (material)|cork]], and those in the Spanish style were sometimes banded about with [[metal]]. Extant pieces are covered with [[leather]], brocades, or jewel-embroidered [[velvet]]. Often, the fabric of the chopine matched the dress or the shoe, but not always. However, despite being highly decorated, chopines were often hidden under the wearer's skirt and were hidden from any critical observation. Although due to the design of the shoes, they caused the wearer to have a very \"comical walk\".<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAccording to some scholars, chopines caused an unstable and inelegant gait. Noblewomen wearing them were generally accompanied by two servants in order to walk around safely, by supporting themselves on the servants' shoulders.<ref name=\":0\">Bossan, Marie-Jos\u00e8phe. \"The Renaissance\". ''The Art of the Shoe''. Trans. Rebecca Brimacombe. New York: Parkstone, 2012. p. 35. via Google Books. Parkstone International, 08 May 2012. Web. 02 May 2014. <<nowiki>https://books.google.com/books?id=2Ifj9h4Z4YQC&pg=PA35&dq=chopines</nowiki> shoes&hl=en&sa=X&ei=SDhkU_q3H5DZoAS4hoKQAw&ved=0CEYQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=chopines shoes&f=false>.</ref> Other scholars have argued that with practice a woman could walk and even dance gracefully.<ref>Barbara Ravelhofer, ''The Early Stuart Masque: Dance, Costume, and Music'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2006), p. 113, fn 47.</ref> In his dancing manual ''Nobilit\u00e0 di dame'' (1600), the Italian dancing master [[Fabritio Caroso]] writes that with care a woman practiced in wearing her chopines could move \u201cwith grace, seemliness, and beauty\u201d and even \"dance flourishes and [[galliard]] variations\".<ref>[[Fabritio Caroso]], ''Nobilit\u00e0 di dame'' (Venice, 1600), translated as ''Courtly Dance of the Renaissance: Nobilit\u00e0 di dame'', ed. and trans. Julia Sutton and F. Marian Walker (New York, 1995), p. 141.</ref> Chopines were usually put on with the help of two servants.\n\n<!-- Image with unknown copyright status removed: [[Image:MFA chopine.jpg]] -->\nIn the 15th century, chopines were also the style in [[Spain]]. Their popularity in Spain was so great that the larger part of the nation's cork supplies went towards production of the shoes. Some argue{{who|date=April 2015}} that the style originated in Spain, as there are many extant examples and a great amount of pictorial and written reference going back to the 14th century.<ref>[[Anderson, Ruth Matilda]]. ''Hispanic costume, 1480-1530.''</ref> Chopines of the Spanish style were more often conical and symmetric, while their Venetian counterparts are much more artistically carved. That is not to say, however, that Spanish chopines were not adorned; on the contrary, there is evidence of jeweling, gilt lettering along the surround (the material covering the cork or wooden base), tooling, and embroidery on Spanish chopines. \n\nThere are a great many cognates of the word chopine (chapiney, choppins, etc.). However, neither the word chopine nor any word similar to it (chioppino, cioppino, etc.) appears in Florio's dictionaries of either 1598 or 1611. The Italian word, instead, seems to be \"zoccoli\", which likely comes from the Italian word \"zocco,\" meaning a stump or a block of wood. Florio does, however, use the word \"chopinos\" in his English definition of zoccoli.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Geta (footwear)]]\n* [[Pint#Other pints|Chopine, volume]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wiktionary}}\n{{Commonscat|Chopines}}\n* http://www.aands.org/raisedheels\n* http://www.chass.utoronto.ca/~ebernhar/index.shtml\n* http://www.metmuseum.org/toah/ho/08/eustn/hod_1973.114.4a,b.htm\n\n{{footwear}}\n{{Historical clothing}}\n\n[[Category:Historical footwear]]\n[[Category:Medieval costume]]\n[[Category:Shoes]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:Medieval costumetoCategory:Medieval European costumeusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chopine"}
{"title_page": "Disc fibula", "text_new": "[[File:Frankish - Disk Fibula - Walters 571714.jpg|thumb|\"Disk fibula\", ca. 7th century.]]\n[[File:Meister des Registrum Gregorii 001.jpg|thumb|[[Otto I (HRR)|Otto the Great]], portrayed wearing a prominent disc fibula]]\nA '''disc fibula''' or '''disc brooch''' is a type of [[fibula (brooch)|fibula]], that is, a [[brooch]], clip or [[pin]] used to fasten clothing that has a disc-shaped, often richly decorated plate or disc covering the fastener. The terms are mostly used in relation to the [[Middle Ages]] of Europe, especially the earlier part of the period.  They were the most common style of [[Anglo-Saxon brooches]].\n\nIn Scotland, where the need for a fastening at the shoulder lasted into the Renaissance and beyond, a type of silver \"turreted\" brooch for men was still being made in the 16th century and later. The [[Brooch of Lorn]] is the best-known example. \n\n==Continental Europe==\nWell-known fibulae of this type date to the [[Migration Period]] and the centuries either side of it, for example the disc fibulae from [[Soest, Germany|Soest]] or the [[Lower Saxony|Lower Saxon]] village of [[Holle]] in [[Germany]].  Disc fibulae up to over 5 centimetres in diameter were usually part of women's attire in continental Europe in the [[Early Middle Ages]]; much smaller examples were also worn by men, however, from the [[Carolingian era]].\n\nMany disc fibulae have gold ornamentation inlaid with [[gemstone]]s, are [[Vitreous enamel|enamel]]led or [[damascening|damascened]], or are overlaid with gold or silver. The well known [[Pliezhausen brooch]] was once the cover of a disc fibula. An example from the [[Roman era]] is the [[Tangendorf disc brooch]]. The early mediaeval [[Maschen disc brooch]] portrays a figure with a saintly [[aureole]].\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\">\nZ\u00fcrich - Uetliberg - F\u00fcrstengrabh\u00fcgel - Goldscheiben.jpg|Gold disc fibulae from the Sonnenb\u00fchl prince's burial mound ([[La T\u00e8ne period]])\nScheibenfibel.jpg|Alemannian disc fibula of the 6th century with [[almandine]] and bone inlays\nFibulae Aregund MAN87424.jpg|Pair of disc fibulae from the [[Aregund]] grave c. 6th C.\nFibules m\u00e9rovingiennes 01.JPG|Merovingian disc fibulae of the 6th and 7th centuries with gemstones and filigree\n</gallery>\n\n==Anglo-Saxon types==\n{{main|Anglo-Saxon brooches}}\nExamples from [[Anglo-Saxon England]] are usually called \"brooches\" in English.  The [[quoit brooch]] is an early type, using motifs from Late Roman art in base metal. Gold types with stones and elaborate decoration in the continental style appear from the 7th century, though later plain silver, decorated with figurative images and often using [[openwork]], becomes more common. Examples in silver include the [[Fuller Brooch]], [[Strickland Brooch]] and the [[Anglo-Scandinavian]] [[\u00c6dwen's brooch]].\n\nFinds from the early period before Christianization are more common, as Christianity discouraged burial with expensive [[grave goods]].  \n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Sarre BroochDSCF9233.JPG|The Sarre Brooch, a 5th-century Kentish [[quoit brooch]], [[British Museum]]\nFile:Anglo-Saxon Disc Brooch from Monkton on display at the Ashmolean Museum.jpg|Anglo-Saxon brooch, from [[Monkton, Kent]]\nFile:Brit Mus 17sept 005-crop.jpg|Brooch from the [[Pentney Hoard]], in the [[Trewhiddle]] style.\nFile:Brit Mus Fuller Brooch.jpg|Anglo-Saxon [[Fuller Brooch]], 9th-century \n\n</gallery>\n\n== Literature ==\n* M. J. Bode: ''Germanische Scheibenfibeln. Ein kurzer \u00dcberblick \u00fcber den Forschungsstand ausgew\u00e4hlter Formen.'' In: J\u00fcrgen Kunow (ed.): ''100 Jahre Fibelformen nach Oskar Almgren.'' W\u00fcnsdorf, 1998, pp. 321\u2013338, {{ISBN|3-910011-17-9}}.\n* Heinrich Beck (ed.): ''Fibel und Fibeltracht.'' Sonderdruck aus [[Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde]]. Berlin, 2000, {{ISBN|3-11-016858-8}}.\n* [[Leslie Webster (art historian)|Webster, Leslie]], ''Anglo-Saxon Art'', 2012, British Museum Press, {{ISBN|9780714128092}}\n\n== Weblinks ==\n* {{BAM/DDB|Scheibenfibel}}\n* {{Spk-digital}}\n\n[[Category:Archaeological artifacts]]\n[[Category:Brooches]]\n[[Category:Medieval European costume]]\n[[Category:Migration Period]]\n[[Category:Merovingian art]]\n[[Category:Carolingian art]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Saxon art]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Frankish - Disk Fibula - Walters 571714.jpg|thumb|\"Disk fibula\", ca. 7th century.]]\n[[File:Meister des Registrum Gregorii 001.jpg|thumb|[[Otto I (HRR)|Otto the Great]], portrayed wearing a prominent disc fibula]]\nA '''disc fibula''' or '''disc brooch''' is a type of [[fibula (brooch)|fibula]], that is, a [[brooch]], clip or [[pin]] used to fasten clothing that has a disc-shaped, often richly decorated plate or disc covering the fastener. The terms are mostly used in relation to the [[Middle Ages]] of Europe, especially the earlier part of the period.  They were the most common style of [[Anglo-Saxon brooches]].\n\nIn Scotland, where the need for a fastening at the shoulder lasted into the Renaissance and beyond, a type of silver \"turreted\" brooch for men was still being made in the 16th century and later. The [[Brooch of Lorn]] is the best-known example. \n\n==Continental Europe==\nWell-known fibulae of this type date to the [[Migration Period]] and the centuries either side of it, for example the disc fibulae from [[Soest, Germany|Soest]] or the [[Lower Saxony|Lower Saxon]] village of [[Holle]] in [[Germany]].  Disc fibulae up to over 5 centimetres in diameter were usually part of women's attire in continental Europe in the [[Early Middle Ages]]; much smaller examples were also worn by men, however, from the [[Carolingian era]].\n\nMany disc fibulae have gold ornamentation inlaid with [[gemstone]]s, are [[Vitreous enamel|enamel]]led or [[damascening|damascened]], or are overlaid with gold or silver. The well known [[Pliezhausen brooch]] was once the cover of a disc fibula. An example from the [[Roman era]] is the [[Tangendorf disc brooch]]. The early mediaeval [[Maschen disc brooch]] portrays a figure with a saintly [[aureole]].\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\">\nZ\u00fcrich - Uetliberg - F\u00fcrstengrabh\u00fcgel - Goldscheiben.jpg|Gold disc fibulae from the Sonnenb\u00fchl prince's burial mound ([[La T\u00e8ne period]])\nScheibenfibel.jpg|Alemannian disc fibula of the 6th century with [[almandine]] and bone inlays\nFibulae Aregund MAN87424.jpg|Pair of disc fibulae from the [[Aregund]] grave c. 6th C.\nFibules m\u00e9rovingiennes 01.JPG|Merovingian disc fibulae of the 6th and 7th centuries with gemstones and filigree\n</gallery>\n\n==Anglo-Saxon types==\n{{main|Anglo-Saxon brooches}}\nExamples from [[Anglo-Saxon England]] are usually called \"brooches\" in English.  The [[quoit brooch]] is an early type, using motifs from Late Roman art in base metal. Gold types with stones and elaborate decoration in the continental style appear from the 7th century, though later plain silver, decorated with figurative images and often using [[openwork]], becomes more common. Examples in silver include the [[Fuller Brooch]], [[Strickland Brooch]] and the [[Anglo-Scandinavian]] [[\u00c6dwen's brooch]].\n\nFinds from the early period before Christianization are more common, as Christianity discouraged burial with expensive [[grave goods]].  \n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"200px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Sarre BroochDSCF9233.JPG|The Sarre Brooch, a 5th-century Kentish [[quoit brooch]], [[British Museum]]\nFile:Anglo-Saxon Disc Brooch from Monkton on display at the Ashmolean Museum.jpg|Anglo-Saxon brooch, from [[Monkton, Kent]]\nFile:Brit Mus 17sept 005-crop.jpg|Brooch from the [[Pentney Hoard]], in the [[Trewhiddle]] style.\nFile:Brit Mus Fuller Brooch.jpg|Anglo-Saxon [[Fuller Brooch]], 9th-century \n\n</gallery>\n\n== Literature ==\n* M. J. Bode: ''Germanische Scheibenfibeln. Ein kurzer \u00dcberblick \u00fcber den Forschungsstand ausgew\u00e4hlter Formen.'' In: J\u00fcrgen Kunow (ed.): ''100 Jahre Fibelformen nach Oskar Almgren.'' W\u00fcnsdorf, 1998, pp. 321\u2013338, {{ISBN|3-910011-17-9}}.\n* Heinrich Beck (ed.): ''Fibel und Fibeltracht.'' Sonderdruck aus [[Reallexikon der Germanischen Altertumskunde]]. Berlin, 2000, {{ISBN|3-11-016858-8}}.\n* [[Leslie Webster (art historian)|Webster, Leslie]], ''Anglo-Saxon Art'', 2012, British Museum Press, {{ISBN|9780714128092}}\n\n== Weblinks ==\n* {{BAM/DDB|Scheibenfibel}}\n* {{Spk-digital}}\n\n[[Category:Archaeological artifacts]]\n[[Category:Brooches]]\n[[Category:Medieval costume]]\n[[Category:Migration Period]]\n[[Category:Merovingian art]]\n[[Category:Carolingian art]]\n[[Category:Anglo-Saxon art]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:Medieval costumetoCategory:Medieval European costumeusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disc_fibula"}
{"title_page": "Wimple", "text_new": "{{short description|Ancient form of female headdress}}\n{{About|the women's headgear|the Torah binder|wimpel}}\n[[File:RCampin.jpg|thumb|A wimple as shown in ''Portrait of a Woman'', circa 1430-1435, by [[Robert Campin]] (1375/1379\u20131444), National Gallery, London. The cloth is 4-[[Ply (layer)|ply]] and the pins holding it in place are visible at the top of the head.]]\n[[File:St Georges Trotton 14.jpg|thumb|[[Monumental brass]] of Margaret, Lady Camoys (d.1310), St George's Church, Trotton, West Sussex. This is the earliest surviving brass of a female figure in England.<ref>Macklin, Herbert Walter & Page-Phillips, John, (Eds.), 1969, p.68[https://archive.org/stream/monumentalbrass00mackgoog#page/n75/mode/2up]</ref> She wears around her neck a wimple (or gorget) which hides the chin and sides of the face. This style of dress continued in fashion until the end of the reign of King Edward III (1327-1377).<ref>Macklin, Herbert Walter & Page-Phillips, John, (Eds.), 1969, p.69</ref>]]\nA '''wimple''' is a medieval form of female [[hat|headdress]], formed of a large piece of cloth worn around the [[neck]] and [[chin]], and covering the top of the [[Human head|head]]. Its use developed in early [[medieval Europe]]. At many stages of medieval [[Christianity|Christian]] culture it was unseemly for a married woman to show her hair. A wimple might be elaborately starched, and creased and folded in prescribed ways, and later elaborated versions were supported on wire or wicker framing, such as the [[cornette]].\n\nItalian women abandoned their head cloths in the 15th century, or replaced them with transparent [[gauze]], and showed their elaborate braids. Both elaborate braiding and elaborately laundered clothes demonstrated status, in that such grooming was being performed by others. Today the wimple is worn by certain [[nun]]s who retain a traditional [[Religious habit|habit]].<ref>{{cite web | author=Heron, Lynford | date=January 18, 2003 | title=Woman, Prayer & Head Covering | url=http://www.centurionministry.org/body/head-covering.asp | publisher=Centurion Ministry | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100318021738/http://www.centurionministry.org/body/head-covering.asp | archivedate=2010-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==In literature==\nThe [[Wife of Bath]] and the [[Priory|Prioress]] are depicted wearing wimples in the ''[[Canterbury Tales]]'' of [[Geoffrey Chaucer]] (c. 1343\u20131400).\n\nThe [[King James Version]] of the [[Bible]] explicitly lists wimples in [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 3:22 as one of a list of female fineries; however, the Hebrew word \"mi\u1e6dpa\u1e25oth\" (\u05de\u05b4\u05d8\u05b0\u05e4\u05b8\u05bc\u05d7\u05d5\u05b9\u05ea) means \"[[kerchief]]\".\n\n==See also==\n* [[Christian headcovering]]\n* [[Headpiece]]\n* [[Headscarf]] \n* [[Hijab]], the Islamic head covering worn by Muslim women\n* [[Veil]]\n* [[Guimpe]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n{{Historical clothing}}\n[[Category:History of clothing (Western fashion)]]\n[[Category:Catholic religious clothing]]\n[[Category:Headgear]]\n[[Category:Medieval European costume]]\n[[Category:Belarusian clothing]]\n[[Category:Religious headgear]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian clothing]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ancient form of female headdress}}\n{{About|the women's headgear|the Torah binder|wimpel}}\n[[File:RCampin.jpg|thumb|A wimple as shown in ''Portrait of a Woman'', circa 1430-1435, by [[Robert Campin]] (1375/1379\u20131444), National Gallery, London. The cloth is 4-[[Ply (layer)|ply]] and the pins holding it in place are visible at the top of the head.]]\n[[File:St Georges Trotton 14.jpg|thumb|[[Monumental brass]] of Margaret, Lady Camoys (d.1310), St George's Church, Trotton, West Sussex. This is the earliest surviving brass of a female figure in England.<ref>Macklin, Herbert Walter & Page-Phillips, John, (Eds.), 1969, p.68[https://archive.org/stream/monumentalbrass00mackgoog#page/n75/mode/2up]</ref> She wears around her neck a wimple (or gorget) which hides the chin and sides of the face. This style of dress continued in fashion until the end of the reign of King Edward III (1327-1377).<ref>Macklin, Herbert Walter & Page-Phillips, John, (Eds.), 1969, p.69</ref>]]\nA '''wimple''' is a medieval form of female [[hat|headdress]], formed of a large piece of cloth worn around the [[neck]] and [[chin]], and covering the top of the [[Human head|head]]. Its use developed in early [[medieval Europe]]. At many stages of medieval [[Christianity|Christian]] culture it was unseemly for a married woman to show her hair. A wimple might be elaborately starched, and creased and folded in prescribed ways, and later elaborated versions were supported on wire or wicker framing, such as the [[cornette]].\n\nItalian women abandoned their head cloths in the 15th century, or replaced them with transparent [[gauze]], and showed their elaborate braids. Both elaborate braiding and elaborately laundered clothes demonstrated status, in that such grooming was being performed by others. Today the wimple is worn by certain [[nun]]s who retain a traditional [[Religious habit|habit]].<ref>{{cite web | author=Heron, Lynford | date=January 18, 2003 | title=Woman, Prayer & Head Covering | url=http://www.centurionministry.org/body/head-covering.asp | publisher=Centurion Ministry | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100318021738/http://www.centurionministry.org/body/head-covering.asp | archivedate=2010-03-18}}</ref>\n\n==In literature==\nThe [[Wife of Bath]] and the [[Priory|Prioress]] are depicted wearing wimples in the ''[[Canterbury Tales]]'' of [[Geoffrey Chaucer]] (c. 1343\u20131400).\n\nThe [[King James Version]] of the [[Bible]] explicitly lists wimples in [[Book of Isaiah|Isaiah]] 3:22 as one of a list of female fineries; however, the Hebrew word \"mi\u1e6dpa\u1e25oth\" (\u05de\u05b4\u05d8\u05b0\u05e4\u05b8\u05bc\u05d7\u05d5\u05b9\u05ea) means \"[[kerchief]]\".\n\n==See also==\n* [[Christian headcovering]]\n* [[Headpiece]]\n* [[Headscarf]] \n* [[Hijab]], the Islamic head covering worn by Muslim women\n* [[Veil]]\n* [[Guimpe]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n{{Historical clothing}}\n[[Category:History of clothing (Western fashion)]]\n[[Category:Catholic religious clothing]]\n[[Category:Headgear]]\n[[Category:Medieval costume]]\n[[Category:Belarusian clothing]]\n[[Category:Religious headgear]]\n[[Category:Ukrainian clothing]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:Medieval costumetoCategory:Medieval European costumeusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wimple"}
{"title_page": "Kirtle", "text_new": "[[File:Orazio Gentileschi - Il suonatore di liuto (National Gallery of Art).jpg|right|thumb|250px|The luteplayer wears a yellow kirtle over her smock, 1626.]]\n{{Wiktionary|1=kirtle}}\n\nA '''kirtle''' (sometimes called [[cotte]], cotehardie) is a garment that was worn by men and women in the [[Middle Ages]]. It eventually became a one-piece garment worn by women from the late Middle Ages into the [[Baroque]] period.  The kirtle was typically worn over a [[chemise]] or [[smock (garment)|smock]], which acted as a slip, and under the formal outer garment or [[gown]]/[[surcoat]].\n\nKirtles were part of fashionable attire into the middle of the sixteenth century, and remained part of country or middle-class clothing into the seventeenth century.\n\nKirtles began as loose garments without a waist seam, changing to tightly fitted supportive garments in the [[1300\u20131400 in fashion|14th century]]. Later kirtles could be constructed by combining a fitted [[bodice]] with a skirt gathered or pleated into the waist seam.  Kirtles could lace up the front, back or side-back, with some rare cases of side lacing, all depending on the fashion of the day/place and what kind of gown was to be worn over it. Kirtles could be embellished with a variety of decorations including gold, silk, tassels, and knobs.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Walter|first=Thornbury|title=The Costume of English Women from the Heptarchy to the Present Day. Chapter III. Henry VII. Henry VIII|journal=The Art Journal|year=1875\u20131887|volume=2|series=New Series|pages=173\u2013177|jstor=20568908}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dirndl]]\n*[[Girdle]]\n*[[Jumper_(dress)|Jumper]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Arnold, Janet:  ''Queen Elizabeth's Wardrobe Unlock'd'', W S Maney and Son Ltd, Leeds 1988. {{ISBN|0-901286-20-6}}\n*Arnold, Janet: ''Patterns of Fashion: the cut and construction of clothes for men and women 1560-1620'', Macmillan 1985. Revised edition 1986. ({{ISBN|0-89676-083-9}})\n*Ashelford, Jane: ''The Art of Dress: Clothing and Society 1500-1914'', Abrams, 1996. {{ISBN|0-8109-6317-5}}  \n*Ashelford, Jane. ''The Visual History of Costume: The Sixteenth Century''. 1983 edition ({{ISBN|0-89676-076-6}}), 1994 reprint ({{ISBN|0-7134-6828-9}}).\n*Hearn, Karen, ed. ''Dynasties: Painting in Tudor and Jacobean England 1530-1630.  New York: Rizzoli, 1995.  {{ISBN|0-8478-1940-X}}.\n* [[The Passionate Shepherd to His Love]] poem by [[Christopher Marlowe]], in the 1590s.\n\n{{Historical clothing|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:14th-century fashion]]\n[[Category:Undergarments]]\n[[Category:Dresses]]\n[[Category:Gowns]]\n[[Category:Medieval European costume]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Orazio Gentileschi - Il suonatore di liuto (National Gallery of Art).jpg|right|thumb|250px|The luteplayer wears a yellow kirtle over her smock, 1626.]]\n{{Wiktionary|1=kirtle}}\n\nA '''kirtle''' (sometimes called [[cotte]], cotehardie) is a garment that was worn by men and women in the [[Middle Ages]]. It eventually became a one-piece garment worn by women from the late Middle Ages into the [[Baroque]] period.  The kirtle was typically worn over a [[chemise]] or [[smock (garment)|smock]], which acted as a slip, and under the formal outer garment or [[gown]]/[[surcoat]].\n\nKirtles were part of fashionable attire into the middle of the sixteenth century, and remained part of country or middle-class clothing into the seventeenth century.\n\nKirtles began as loose garments without a waist seam, changing to tightly fitted supportive garments in the [[1300\u20131400 in fashion|14th century]]. Later kirtles could be constructed by combining a fitted [[bodice]] with a skirt gathered or pleated into the waist seam.  Kirtles could lace up the front, back or side-back, with some rare cases of side lacing, all depending on the fashion of the day/place and what kind of gown was to be worn over it. Kirtles could be embellished with a variety of decorations including gold, silk, tassels, and knobs.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Walter|first=Thornbury|title=The Costume of English Women from the Heptarchy to the Present Day. Chapter III. Henry VII. Henry VIII|journal=The Art Journal|year=1875\u20131887|volume=2|series=New Series|pages=173\u2013177|jstor=20568908}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Dirndl]]\n*[[Girdle]]\n*[[Jumper_(dress)|Jumper]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*Arnold, Janet:  ''Queen Elizabeth's Wardrobe Unlock'd'', W S Maney and Son Ltd, Leeds 1988. {{ISBN|0-901286-20-6}}\n*Arnold, Janet: ''Patterns of Fashion: the cut and construction of clothes for men and women 1560-1620'', Macmillan 1985. Revised edition 1986. ({{ISBN|0-89676-083-9}})\n*Ashelford, Jane: ''The Art of Dress: Clothing and Society 1500-1914'', Abrams, 1996. {{ISBN|0-8109-6317-5}}  \n*Ashelford, Jane. ''The Visual History of Costume: The Sixteenth Century''. 1983 edition ({{ISBN|0-89676-076-6}}), 1994 reprint ({{ISBN|0-7134-6828-9}}).\n*Hearn, Karen, ed. ''Dynasties: Painting in Tudor and Jacobean England 1530-1630.  New York: Rizzoli, 1995.  {{ISBN|0-8478-1940-X}}.\n* [[The Passionate Shepherd to His Love]] poem by [[Christopher Marlowe]], in the 1590s.\n\n{{Historical clothing|state=expanded}}\n\n[[Category:14th-century fashion]]\n[[Category:Undergarments]]\n[[Category:Dresses]]\n[[Category:Gowns]]\n[[Category:Medieval costume]]\n", "name_user": "Fayenatic london", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:Medieval costumetoCategory:Medieval European costumeusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kirtle"}
{"title_page": "Jabal Haraz", "text_new": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = Jabal Haraz\n| native_name       = {{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632}}\n| native_name_lang  = ar\n| photo             = Yemen (11462772954).jpg\n| photo_caption     = A building with terraces overlooks the side of one of the Haraz mountains\n| country           = {{YEM}}\n| region_type       = \n| region            = Asia\n| border            =\n| highest           = \n| elevation_m       = 3,000\n| highest_location  = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|15.1667|N|43.7500|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n| range_coordinates =\n| length_km         = \n| geology           =\n| period            =\n| orogeny           =\n| map               = Yemen#Middle East#Asia\n| map_image         = \n| map_caption       = \n}}\n\n'''Jabal Haraz''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632|Jabal \u1e24ar\u0101z}}) is a mountainous region of [[Yemen]], between [[Sanaa]] and [[Al Hudaydah|Al-Hudaydah]], which is considered to be within of the [[Sarawat Mountains|Sarat range]].<ref name=\"CookFarmer2013\">{{cite book |last1=Cook |first1=John |last2=Farmer |first2=G. Thomas |title=Climate Change Science: A Modern Synthesis |volume=1 \u2013 The Physical Climate |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer Science & Business Media]] |chapter=VI: Land and Its Climates |page=334 |isbn=9-4007-5757-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tbtEAAAAQBAJ&dq=sarawat+mountains&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2013-01-12}}</ref> In the 11th century, it was the stronghold of the [[Sulaihid State|Sulaihid]] dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive today.<ref name=unesco>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1722/ |title=Jabal Haraz |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |date=2002-07-08 |access-date=2009-03-24}}</ref> They include [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]], the highest mountain in Yemen and the [[Arabian Peninsula]].<ref name=\"Laughlin2008\">{{cite book |last=McLaughlin |first=Daniel |title=Yemen |publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]] |chapter=1: Background |page=3 |isbn=978-1-8416-2212-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQvhZaEVzjcC&pg |year=2008}}</ref>\n\n== History and location ==\nBecause of its location between the [[Tihamah]] coastal plain and Sanaa, this mountainous area has always been strategically important. A caravan stopping point during the [[Himyarite Kingdom]], the Haraz was later the stronghold of the [[Sulayhid dynasty]], which was established in Yemen in 1037. Then and subsequently the population have been [[Ism'aili]] [[Shia Islam|Shi'ite]] [[Muslim]]s.\n\nHaraz is as famous for its fortified villages which cling to nearly inaccessible rocky peaks. Their imposing architecture meets two needs: defending the villagers, while leaving plenty of space for crops. Each town is built like a castle; the houses, themselves, form the wall, equipped with one or two easily defensible doors. Constructed from sandstone and basalt, the buildings are integrated into the landscape and it is difficult to tell where the rock and the village begins or ends. The mountain is divided into terraces of a few acres or more, separated by walls sometimes several meters high. On these terraced fields grow alfalfa for livestock, millet, lentils, large areas for coffee and [[Khat|qat]].\n\nWithin a day's journey are [[Bani Murrah]] and other villages located on the ridge overlooking [[Manakhah]]. Manakhah is the heart of mountain range, a large town whose market attracts villagers from the entire neighbourhood. [[Al Hajjara]], to the west of Manakhah, is a walled village whose citadel was founded in the 12th century by the Sulayhids. From there, other villages are accessible, such as [[Bayt al-Qamus]]  and [[Bayt Shimran]]. The village of [[Hutaib]] is built on a platform of red sandstone, facing a view of terraced hills which host a score of villages. Here also is the mausoleum of the third Yemeni ''[[Da'i al-Mutlaq]]'' [[Hatim ibn Ibrahim]]. [[Mustaali|Bohras]] from [[India]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Madagascar]] and other countries gather here.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n== World Heritage Status ==\nThis area was added to the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage]] Tentative List on July 8, 2002, in the mixed (cultural and natural) category, as a site that has \"outstanding universal value\".<ref name=unesco/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Haraz 200612 Yemen-115 (353667843).jpg|A terraced mountain side in [[Al Mahwit Governorate]] near [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]] (the highest mountain in the [[Arabian Peninsula]])\nFile:\u0645\u0646\u062a\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062f\u0633\u064a\u0629 - panoramio.jpg|Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb is behind the mountain in the background, facing west of southern [[Sanaa]]\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (12633745063).jpg|Jabal Haraz terraces\nFile:Manakha 01.jpg|[[Manakhah]]\nFile:Haraz Mtns, Yemen (13970993973).jpg|Buildings at the base of a mountain\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (14616928081).jpg|Fortified settlement amid the mountains\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ad Dahrah]], located in the Haraz, the stronghold of the Sulaihid dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive to this day\n* [[Geology of Yemen]]\n* [[Hajhir Mountains]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120922020555/http://www.lonelyplanet.com/yemen/the-harazmountains Lonely Planet]\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Jabal Haraz}}\n* [https://www.architecturerevived.com/architectural-beauty-out-of-poverty-jabal-haraz-yemen/ Architecture Revived: Architectural Beauty out of Poverty, Jabal Haraz Yemen]\n* [http://medomed.org/featured_item/jabal-bura-and-jabal-haraz-the-mountanous-cultural-landscape-of-yemen-yemen/ Med-O-Med: Cultural landscapes: Jabal Bura and Jabal Haraz, Yemen]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DcgXBQlPUJs Jabal Haraz] ([[YouTube]])\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qqJSqAjtbCA Yemen - Haraz Mountains]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mbooIXhPq-E Yemen 2008 Jebel Haraz]\n\n{{Tourist attractions in Yemen}}\n{{Mountains in the Arabian Peninsula}}\n\n[[Category:Jabal Haraz|*]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of mainland Yemen]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox mountain\n| name              = Jabal Haraz\n| native_name       = {{lang|ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632}}\n| native_name_lang  = ar\n| photo             = Yemen (11462772954).jpg\n| photo_caption     = A building with terraces overlooks the side of one of the Haraz mountains\n| country           = {{YEM}}\n| region_type       = \n| region            = Asia\n| border            =\n| highest           = \n| elevation_m       = 3,000\n| highest_location  = \n| coordinates       = {{coord|15.1667|N|43.7500|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n| range_coordinates =\n| length_km         = \n| geology           =\n| period            =\n| orogeny           =\n| map               = Yemen#Middle East#Asia\n| map_image         = \n| map_caption       = \n}}\n\n'''Jabal Haraz''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u064e\u0628\u064e\u0644 \u062d\u064e\u0631\u064e\u0627\u0632|Jabal \u1e24ar\u0101z}}) is a mountain region of [[Yemen]], between [[Sana'a]] and [[Al Hudaydah|Al-Hudaydah]]. In the 11th century, it was the stronghold of the [[Sulaihid State|Sulaihid]] dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive today.<ref name=unesco>{{cite web |url=https://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/1722/ |title=Jabal Haraz |publisher=UNESCO World Heritage Centre |date=2002-07-08 |access-date=2009-03-24}}</ref> They include [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]], the highest mountain in Yemen and the [[Arabian Peninsula]],<ref name=\"Laughlin2008\">{{cite book |last=McLaughlin |first=Daniel |title=Yemen |publisher=[[Bradt Travel Guides]] |chapter=1: Background |page=3 |isbn=978-1-8416-2212-5 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eQvhZaEVzjcC&pg |year=2008}}</ref> and are considered part of the [[Sarawat Mountains|Sarat range]].<ref name=\"CookFarmer2013\">{{cite book |last1=Cook |first1=John |last2=Farmer |first2=G. Thomas |title=Climate Change Science: A Modern Synthesis |volume=1 \u2013 The Physical Climate |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer Science & Business Media]] |chapter=VI: Land and Its Climates |page=334 |isbn=9-4007-5757-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tbtEAAAAQBAJ&dq=sarawat+mountains&source=gbs_navlinks_s |date=2013-01-12}}</ref>\n\n== History and location ==\nBecause of its location between the [[Tihamah]] coastal plain and Sanaa, this mountainous area has always been strategically important. A caravan stopping point during the [[Himyarite Kingdom]], the Haraz was later the stronghold of the [[Sulayhid dynasty]], which was established in Yemen in 1037. Then and subsequently the population have been [[Ism'aili]] [[Shia Islam|Shi'ite]] [[Muslim]]s.\n\nHaraz is as famous for its fortified villages which cling to nearly inaccessible rocky peaks. Their imposing architecture meets two needs: defending the villagers, while leaving plenty of space for crops. Each town is built like a castle; the houses, themselves, form the wall, equipped with one or two easily defensible doors. Constructed from sandstone and basalt, the buildings are integrated into the landscape and it is difficult to tell where the rock and the village begins or ends. The mountain is divided into terraces of a few acres or more, separated by walls sometimes several meters high. On these terraced fields grow alfalfa for livestock, millet, lentils, large areas for coffee and [[Khat|qat]].\n\nWithin a day's journey are [[Bani Murrah]] and other villages located on the ridge overlooking [[Manakhah]]. Manakhah is the heart of mountain range, a large town whose market attracts villagers from the entire neighbourhood. [[Al Hajjara]], to the west of Manakhah, is a walled village whose citadel was founded in the 12th century by the Sulayhids. From there, other villages are accessible, such as [[Bayt al-Qamus]]  and [[Bayt Shimran]]. The village of [[Hutaib]] is built on a platform of red sandstone, facing a view of terraced hills which host a score of villages. Here also is the mausoleum of the third Yemeni ''[[Da'i al-Mutlaq]]'' [[Hatim ibn Ibrahim]]. [[Mustaali|Bohras]] from [[India]], [[Sri Lanka]], [[Madagascar]] and other countries gather here.{{citation needed|date=December 2018}}\n\n== World Heritage Status ==\nThis area was added to the [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage]] Tentative List on July 8, 2002, in the mixed (cultural and natural) category, as a site that has \"outstanding universal value\".<ref name=unesco/>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Haraz 200612 Yemen-115 (353667843).jpg|A terraced mountain side in [[Al Mahwit Governorate]] near [[Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb]] (the highest mountain in the [[Arabian Peninsula]])\nFile:\u0645\u0646\u062a\u0632\u0629 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0627\u062f\u0633\u064a\u0629 - panoramio.jpg|Jabal An-Nabi Shu'ayb is behind the mountain in the background, facing west of southern [[Sanaa]]\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (12633745063).jpg|Jabal Haraz terraces\nFile:Manakha 01.jpg|[[Manakhah]]\nFile:Haraz Mtns, Yemen (13970993973).jpg|Buildings at the base of a mountain\nFile:Haraz Mountains, Yemen (14616928081).jpg|Fortified settlement amid the mountains\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Ad Dahrah]], located in the Haraz, the stronghold of the Sulaihid dynasty, many of whose buildings still survive to this day\n* [[Geology of Yemen]]\n* [[Hajhir Mountains]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120922020555/http://www.lonelyplanet.com/yemen/the-harazmountains Lonely Planet]\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Jabal Haraz}}\n* [https://www.architecturerevived.com/architectural-beauty-out-of-poverty-jabal-haraz-yemen/ Architecture Revived: Architectural Beauty out of Poverty, Jabal Haraz Yemen]\n* [http://medomed.org/featured_item/jabal-bura-and-jabal-haraz-the-mountanous-cultural-landscape-of-yemen-yemen/ Med-O-Med: Cultural landscapes: Jabal Bura and Jabal Haraz, Yemen]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DcgXBQlPUJs Jabal Haraz] ([[YouTube]])\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qqJSqAjtbCA Yemen - Haraz Mountains]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mbooIXhPq-E Yemen 2008 Jebel Haraz]\n\n{{Tourist attractions in Yemen}}\n{{Mountains in the Arabian Peninsula}}\n\n[[Category:Jabal Haraz|*]]\n[[Category:Mountain ranges of mainland Yemen]]\n[[Category:World Heritage Tentative List]]\n", "name_user": "Leo1pard", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jabal_Haraz"}
{"title_page": "Mark Labbett", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mark Labbett\n| birth_name         = Mark Andrew Labbett\n| other_names        ''The Beast''\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1965|8|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = Tiverton, Devon, [[England]]<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ipO41k7PZMc|title=Mark Labbett Welsh Radio Interview|date=5 February 2012|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n| occupation         = [[Television personality]]\n| height             = 6 ft 7 in (1.98 m)\n| weight             = {{convert|380|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite tweet | author= Labbett, Mark | user= MarkLabbett | number= 493797035934765056| date=29 July 2014| title=where is my invite?? at a legitimate 360lbs I am by far the biggest heel on UK television!}}</ref>\n| spouse             = Katie Labbett <small>(m. 2014)</small>\n| children           = 1\n| credits            = {{nowrap|''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase]]'' (2009\u2013 )<br> ''[[The Chase (U.S. game show)|The Chase USA]]'' (2013\u20132015)<br>''[[The Chase Australia]]'' (2016\u2013 )}}\n| website            = [https://web.archive.org/web/20120902195523/http://marklabbett.co.uk/ marklabbett.co.uk]\n}}\n'''Mark Andrew Labbett'''<ref>{{Cite tweet |user= MarkLabbett | author= Labbett, Mark|  number= 963852096113119234| title=In that case, for posterity, Mark Andrew Labbett :) |date= 14 February 2018| language= en| access-date=14 February 2018}}</ref> (born 15 August 1965) is a [[British people|British]] quizzer, [[television personality]] and radio 1 DJ. He is a \"chaser\" on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] game show ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase]]'', starting in 2009. He subsequently appeared on the [[The Chase (American game show)|American version]] as their sole chaser in 2013 and as one of six chasers on the [[The Chase Australia|Australian version]] since 2016.<ref name=\"Australia2016\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/television/the-chase-australias-newest-uk-recruit-mark-labbett-is-already-doing-a-number-on-rivals-at-nine/story-fni0cc2c-1227626548676| title=The Chase Australia's newest UK recruit Mark Labbett is already doing a number on rivals at Nine| work=The Sunday Telegraoh | place= Australia|first=Holly|last=Byrnes|date=29 November 2015|accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref> His nickname on these shows is \"The Beast\".  \n\nLabbett has appeared as a contestant on several other television quiz shows and is a regular in quizzing competitions.\n\nThe Beast appeared on Chris Stark and Scott Mills radio 1 breakfast show in April 2020,  completing a 20 minute DJ set from his study, claiming it could not be done from his kitchen as \u201cevery 10 seconds you would hear the sound of him eating something.\u201d\n\n== Early life ==\nMark Andrew Labbett was born in [[Tiverton, Devon]], to Carolyn and Jon Labbett.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=DWjZfs9IstcvvZE2%2BlezkQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=1 February 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> He has two younger brothers, Paul and Philip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=WAVwtipxmR0Dkl0Z4401eA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=2 February 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=egJbofNXqmUuf0hCn9hDhQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=2 February 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>\n\nLabbett obtained a [[Master of Arts|Master of Arts degree]] in [[mathematics]] from [[Exeter College, Oxford]], a [[Postgraduate Certificate in Education]] (PGCE) in secondary education from the [[University of Exeter]] and legal [[Common Professional Examination|CPE]] and [[Legal Practice Course|LPC]] qualifications from the University of Glamorgan (now the [[University of South Wales]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marklabbett.co.uk/biography.html |title=Biography |work=Mark \"The Beast\" Labbett |accessdate=23 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902195528/http://marklabbett.co.uk/biography.html |archivedate=2 September 2012  }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Teaching ===\nLabbett was a mathematics and physical education supply teacher.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/peoplesquiz/about/mark_labett.shtml |title=The People's Quiz 2007 |publisher=BBC |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113062346/http://www.bbc.co.uk/peoplesquiz/about/mark_labett.shtml |archivedate=13 January 2008 |date=April 2007 |accessdate= 23 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Quizzing ===\nLabbett became interested in quizzing when working at [[Butlins]] holiday camp, where he supplemented his income with winnings from the [[quiz machine]]s.<ref name=\"lucky\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2007/jan/27/consumernews.moneysupplement|title=Lucky break? Don't leave it to chance|last=Papworth|first=Jill|date=27 January 2007|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref> His [[pub quiz]] team won a weekend in [[Paris]] in April 2001 after competing in the national competition Jumbo Quiz.<ref>{{cite news |first=Will |last=Smale|title=PUB QUIZ TEAM IS GIVEN PRIZE GRILLING |work=South Wales Echo |date=17 April 2001 |publisher=Western Mail and Echo Ltd |page=16}}</ref>\n\nHe works as a question writer for Redtooth, a quiz company from [[Barlborough]] near [[Chesterfield]] in [[Derbyshire]]. After two years of part-time work as a promoter for them, he moved to [[South Yorkshire]] in 2013 in order to work more often with them, but he no longer lives there.\n\nLabbett appeared on ''[[Mastermind (TV series)|Mastermind]]'' in 1999, where his specialist subject was the [[Olympic Games]].<ref name=\"wm\">{{cite news |first=Clare |last=Hutchinson |work=The Western Mail |date=13 October 2009 |title='Come on, Paxman, if you think you're hard enough...' says wicked Humphrys ; Questions at 20 paces in quiz duel \u2013 and we'll even make it easy for you Humphrys |publisher=Western Mail and Echo Ltd |page=14}}</ref> He appeared again on ''Mastermind'' in 2000, with the animated television show ''[[The Simpsons]]'' as his specialist subject.<ref>{{cite news |first=KAREN |last=PRICE |title=MASTERMIND ACCUSED OF SELLING OUT IN RATINGS FIGHT |work=Western Mail |date=6 August 2004 |page=10 |publisher=Western Mail and Echo Ltd|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/2004/08/06/mastermind-accused-of-selling-out-in-ratings-fight-91466-14502345/2/}}</ref> Also in 2000, he competed on ''[[Countdown (game show)|Countdown]]'', narrowly losing his first game on a crucial conundrum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiki.apterous.org/Episode_2771|title=Episode 2771 \u2013 Countdown|publisher=}}</ref> In 2001 he appeared on ''[[Stake Out (game show)|Stake Out]]'', where he was the second contestant eliminated during the Face Off round. In 2003, he appeared on ''[[Grand Slam (UK game show)|Grand Slam]]'', where he lost against [[Clive Spate]] in his first match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com:80/entertainment/tv/microsites/G/grandslam/review_03.html|title=Match Review \u2013 Game 01 \u2013 Channel 4 \u2013 Grand Slam|website=Channel 4|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040831151925/http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/G/grandslam/review_03.html|archive-date=31 August 2004|url-status=dead|access-date=10 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he won \u00a3500 on the [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] show ''[[BrainTeaser]]'', and a year later he won \u00a31,500 on BBC One's ''[[SUDO-Q]]''.<ref name=\"lucky\" /> In 2005, he won \u00a332,000 on ''Millionaire Live'', a live version of ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' that toured seaside resorts throughout the summer.<ref name=\"lucky\" /><ref>{{cite news |first= John Paul |last=Hedge |title=Winners walk off with two cars and \u00a316k |work=Herald Express |location=Torquay |date=5 September 2005 |publisher=Herald Express (Torquay) |page=4}}</ref> As captain, he led the Welsh quiz team to fifth place in the 2006 [[European Quizzing Championships]].<ref name=\"bbc\"/> \n\nLabbett's team, the Rugby Boys, won [[BBC Four]]'s ''[[Only Connect]]'' in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=NEWSBRIEF |work=South Wales Echo |date=1 September 2009 |page=6 |publisher=Western Mail and Echo Ltd}}</ref> Other television appearances include ''[[The National Lottery People's Quiz]]'' (2007) where he came second in the grand final,<ref>{{cite news |first=Olav |last=Bjortomt |authorlink=Olav Bjortomt |title=Your starter for \u00a3200,000 (subscription required) |date=23 June 2007 |work=The Times (The Knowledge) |page=33 |publisher=Times Newspapers Limited |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/tv-radio/article2440448.ece}}</ref> ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'',<ref name=\"guard1\">{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Heritage |title=The Chase: how to make the perfect daytime gameshow |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2010/jun/28/the-chase-gameshow-itv |date=28 June 2010 |work=The Guardian |accessdate= 23 June 2012}}</ref> where he won \u00a332,000, ''[[University Challenge]]''<ref name=\"wm\"/> and ''[[Are You an Egghead?]]''.\n\nIn 2012, Labbett was ranked 89th in the [[World Quizzing Championship]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldquizzing.com/results/|title=Results|work=worldquizzing.com|access-date=2 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607192638/http://www.worldquizzing.com/results/|archive-date=7 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Labbett took part in the three-part [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''[[Sugar Free Farm]]'', when he revealed he has false teeth, as a result of eating too much sugar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week4/sugar-free-farm|title=Sugar Free Farm Episode 1|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tv.bt.com/tv/tv-news/the-chases-mark-labbett-reveals-he-wears-false-teeth-due-to-daily-10-bar-chocolate-habit-11364037330556|title=The Chase's Mark Labbett reveals he wears false teeth due to daily 10 bar chocolate habit|newspaper=BT.com|access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref> That same year, it was announced that he would become a producer for Hull-based wrestling promotion [[New Generation Wrestling]] (NGW).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ngwuk.com/news/Labbett/|title=NGW: 'The Beast' comes to NGW|website=www.ngwuk.com|access-date=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== ''The Chase'' ====\n{{See also|The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase (U.S. game show)|The Chase Australia}}\nLabbett is one of the \"chasers\" in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] teatime quiz ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase]]'', first broadcast in 2009 and hosted by [[Bradley Walsh]]. In the show, his nickname is \"The Beast\",<ref name='bristol'>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisissouthwales.co.uk/Quiz-beast-appearance/story-16062113-detail/story.html|title=Quiz beast appearance|date=12 May 2012|work=Bristol Evening Post|page=19|publisher=Bristol United Press}}</ref> a two-pronged nickname referencing both his stature and his surname (Labbett sounds like the French ''la b\u00eate'', meaning \"the beast\").\n\nIn August 2013, Labbett appeared as the only chaser on the [[The Chase (U.S. game show)|U.S. version]] of ''The Chase'' on [[Game Show Network]]. He also appears as one of the seven chasers on the [[The Chase Australia|Australian version]] of ''The Chase'' on the [[Seven Network]], alongside fellow UK chasers [[Anne Hegerty]] and [[Shaun Wallace]].<ref name=\"Australia2016\"/> His weakest subjects are [[horse racing]] and [[soap opera]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RMobd0rLMZc|title=The Chase's Beast Reveals His Quiz Knowledge Achilles Heel \u2013 Lorraine|author=Lorraine|date=23 January 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> He noted that the American version posed far more difficulties for him, as American game shows typically allow far more competent contestants than British or Australian shows; he stated that his most challenging opponent was [[James Holzhauer]], co-winner of the American version of ''The Chase'' and later a famous ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' contestant.<ref name=holzhauerexplains>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/04/james-holzhauer-jeopardy-1-million-win-or-lose/587878/|title=James Holzhauer Explains the Strategy Behind His Jeopardy Winning Streak|last=Pinsker|first=Joe|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=April 24, 2019|accessdate=April 24, 2019|quote=I've got to give ''Jeopardy!'' immense credit, and ''The Chase'' U.S.A. In Britain or Australia, James would not have made it onto television, because he's just too damn good. They would never have him on.}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nLabbett moved to [[Caldicot, Monmouthshire|Caldicot]], [[Monmouthshire]], in 1998 and then to nearby [[Newport, Wales|Newport]] in 2003 before moving to Moorgate, [[Rotherham]], in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/quiz-sensation-successfully-chases-dream-6466365 |title=The Chase quiz sensation Mark 'The Beast' Labbett cracks America |last= Gaskell |first=Simon |date=5 January 2014 |website=[[Wales Online]] |access-date=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Chase's Beast moves to South Yorkshire |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/chase-s-beast-moves-to-south-yorkshire-1-5268888 |newspaper=[[Sheffield Star|The Star]] |location=Sheffield, UK |date=2 January 2013 |access-date=2 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028234446/http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/chase-s-beast-moves-to-south-yorkshire-1-5268888 |archive-date=28 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He resides in or near [[Herefordshire]].<ref>Philips, Jessica (23 October 2015). [http://www.herefordtimes.com/news/13891554.TV_chaser__the_Beast__visits_Herefordshire_tearoom/ \"TV chaser 'the Beast' visits Herefordshire tearoom\"]. ''[[Hereford Times]]''.</ref> He is [[Type-II diabetic]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/866050/The-Chase-Mark-Labbett-life-changing-Type-2-diabetes-diagnosis-weight-loss-diet-ITV|title=The Chase star Mark Labbett reveals life-changing diagnosis: 'No arguments now'| last= Wright|first=Minnie|date=17 October 2017| work=Express.co.uk|access-date= 23 July 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLabbett married his wife, Katie,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3wJuKZsqUfE|title=The Chase's Beast Introduces His Wife Katie |publisher= Loose Women|date=21 August 2017 |via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> who is his second cousin and 27 years his junior, in October 2014 at [[Arundel Cathedral]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Yaqoob |first=Janine |date=11 October 2014 |title=The Chase game show star Mark 'Beast' Labbett marries girl less than half his age |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/chase-star-mark-beast-labbett-4421923 |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |location=London |access-date=2 February 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Winter 2014 Edition |url= http://www.arundelcathedral.org/proclaimer/Proclaimer_Winter_2014.pdf |work= Parish Proclaimer |location=Arundel |date=2014 |access-date=2 February 2016}}</ref> They have a son.<ref>https://www.ok.co.uk/tv/chase-mark-labbett-weight-loss-14359370.amp</ref> The couple reportedly separated in 2019<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/1126035/mark-labbett-wife-katie-marriage-split-cheating-the-chase-itv-latest-news-updates|title=Mark Labbett: The Chase star\u2019s wife Katie breaks silence on their SPLIT 'It's hard'|work=Daily Express|date=12 May 2019|accessdate=27 May 2019| first= Michelle|last=Marshall}}</ref> but reconciled for the sake of their child.<ref>{{Cite web| url= https://metro.co.uk/2019/09/10/chase-star-mark-labbett-confirms-wife-katie-still-together-priority-son-10717301/| title=The Chase star Mark Labbett and wife Katie are back together |last= Deen|first=Sarah|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref>\n\nLabbett's favourite [[association football|football]] team is [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sheffieldtelegraph.co.uk/news/mark-labbett-talked-the-chase-co-star-anne-hegerty-into-im-a-celebrity-get-me-out-of-here-206709 |title= Mark Labbett 'talked' The Chase co-star Anne Hegerty into I'm A Celebrity Get Me Out Of Here| work= Sheffield Telegraph| access-date=2019-11-03|language=en-GB| issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== Television ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Channel\n|-\n| 2009\u2014\n| ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase]]''\n| rowspan=\"5\" |Chaser\n|[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n|-\n| 2011\u2014\n| ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase: Celebrity Specials]]''\n|rowspan |ITV\n|-\n| 2013\u20132015\n| ''[[The Chase (U.S. game show)|The Chase USA]]''\n| [[Game Show Network]]\n|-\n| 2016\u2014\n| ''[[The Chase Australia]]''\n| [[Seven Network|Channel 7]]\n|-\n| 2017\u2014\n| ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Family Chase]]''\n|rowspan | ITV\n|}\n\n=== Guest appearances ===\n*''[[Mastermind (TV series)|Mastermind]]'' (1999, 2000) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Countdown (game show)|Countdown]]'' (2000) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Stake Out (game show)|Stake Out]]'' (2001) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Grand Slam (UK game show)|Grand Slam]]'' (2003) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[BrainTeaser]]'' (2004) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[SUDO-Q]]'' (2005) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[University Challenge]]'' \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' (2006) \u2013 contestant<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/mark-labbett-beast-the-chase-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-video_uk_586f83d8e4b0961f0937b27e|title=\u2018The Chase\u2019 Star Mark Labbett Was On \u2018Who Wants To Be A Millionaire\u2019 (But How Much Did He Win?)|date=6 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n*''[[The National Lottery People's Quiz]]'' (2007) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Are You an Egghead?]]'' (2008) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Only Connect]]'' (2009) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Sugar Free Farm]]'' (2016) \u2013 participant\n*''[[Tipping Point (game show)|Tipping Point: Lucky Stars]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a813061/the-chase-tipping-point-charity-special/|title=The Chase and Tipping Point are crossing over!|date=3 November 2016|publisher=}}</ref> (2016) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Let's Sing and Dance|Let's Sing and Dance for Comic Relief]]'' (2017) \u2013 participant\n*''[[Celebrity Juice]]'' (2017) \u2013 participant\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links == \n{{Portal|Biography|Television}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=3584757|name=Mark Labbett}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.marklabbett.co.uk/}}\n\n{{The Chase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Labbett, Mark}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:People from Tiverton, Devon]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Exeter]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Exeter College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glamorgan]]\n[[Category:English television personalities]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Contestants on British game shows]]\n[[Category:Contestants on University Challenge]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Mark Labbett\n| birth_name         = Mark Andrew Labbett\n| other_names        ''The Beast''\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1965|8|15|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = Tiverton, Devon, [[England]]<ref>{{cite av media|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ipO41k7PZMc|title=Mark Labbett Welsh Radio Interview|date=5 February 2012|work=YouTube}}</ref>\n| occupation         = [[Television personality]]\n| height             = 6 ft 7 in (1.98 m)\n| weight             = {{convert|380|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite tweet | author= Labbett, Mark | user= MarkLabbett | number= 493797035934765056| date=29 July 2014| title=where is my invite?? at a legitimate 360lbs I am by far the biggest heel on UK television!}}</ref>\n| spouse             = Katie Labbett <small>(m. 2014)</small>\n| children           = 1\n| credits            = {{nowrap|''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase]]'' (2009\u2013 )<br> ''[[The Chase (U.S. game show)|The Chase USA]]'' (2013\u20132015)<br>''[[The Chase Australia]]'' (2016\u2013 )}}\n| website            = [https://web.archive.org/web/20120902195523/http://marklabbett.co.uk/ marklabbett.co.uk]\n}}\n'''Mark Andrew Labbett'''<ref>{{Cite tweet |user= MarkLabbett | author= Labbett, Mark|  number= 963852096113119234| title=In that case, for posterity, Mark Andrew Labbett :) |date= 14 February 2018| language= en| access-date=14 February 2018}}</ref> (born 15 August 1965) is a [[British people|British]] quizzer and [[television personality]]. He is a \"chaser\" on the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] game show ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase]]'', starting in 2009. He subsequently appeared on the [[The Chase (American game show)|American version]] as their sole chaser in 2013 and as one of six chasers on the [[The Chase Australia|Australian version]] since 2016.<ref name=\"Australia2016\">{{cite web |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/television/the-chase-australias-newest-uk-recruit-mark-labbett-is-already-doing-a-number-on-rivals-at-nine/story-fni0cc2c-1227626548676| title=The Chase Australia's newest UK recruit Mark Labbett is already doing a number on rivals at Nine| work=The Sunday Telegraoh | place= Australia|first=Holly|last=Byrnes|date=29 November 2015|accessdate=29 November 2015}}</ref> His nickname on these shows is \"The Beast\".  \n\nLabbett has appeared as a contestant on several other television quiz shows and is a regular in quizzing competitions.\n\n== Early life ==\nMark Andrew Labbett was born in [[Tiverton, Devon]], to Carolyn and Jon Labbett.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=DWjZfs9IstcvvZE2%2BlezkQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=1 February 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> He has two younger brothers, Paul and Philip.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=WAVwtipxmR0Dkl0Z4401eA&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=2 February 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=egJbofNXqmUuf0hCn9hDhQ&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=2 February 2016|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref>\n\nLabbett obtained a [[Master of Arts|Master of Arts degree]] in [[mathematics]] from [[Exeter College, Oxford]], a [[Postgraduate Certificate in Education]] (PGCE) in secondary education from the [[University of Exeter]] and legal [[Common Professional Examination|CPE]] and [[Legal Practice Course|LPC]] qualifications from the University of Glamorgan (now the [[University of South Wales]]).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.marklabbett.co.uk/biography.html |title=Biography |work=Mark \"The Beast\" Labbett |accessdate=23 June 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902195528/http://marklabbett.co.uk/biography.html |archivedate=2 September 2012  }}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== Teaching ===\nLabbett was a mathematics and physical education supply teacher.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/peoplesquiz/about/mark_labett.shtml |title=The People's Quiz 2007 |publisher=BBC |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080113062346/http://www.bbc.co.uk/peoplesquiz/about/mark_labett.shtml |archivedate=13 January 2008 |date=April 2007 |accessdate= 23 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Quizzing ===\nLabbett became interested in quizzing when working at [[Butlins]] holiday camp, where he supplemented his income with winnings from the [[quiz machine]]s.<ref name=\"lucky\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/money/2007/jan/27/consumernews.moneysupplement|title=Lucky break? Don't leave it to chance|last=Papworth|first=Jill|date=27 January 2007|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=23 June 2012}}</ref> His [[pub quiz]] team won a weekend in [[Paris]] in April 2001 after competing in the national competition Jumbo Quiz.<ref>{{cite news |first=Will |last=Smale|title=PUB QUIZ TEAM IS GIVEN PRIZE GRILLING |work=South Wales Echo |date=17 April 2001 |publisher=Western Mail and Echo Ltd |page=16}}</ref>\n\nHe works as a question writer for Redtooth, a quiz company from [[Barlborough]] near [[Chesterfield]] in [[Derbyshire]]. After two years of part-time work as a promoter for them, he moved to [[South Yorkshire]] in 2013 in order to work more often with them, but he no longer lives there.\n\nLabbett appeared on ''[[Mastermind (TV series)|Mastermind]]'' in 1999, where his specialist subject was the [[Olympic Games]].<ref name=\"wm\">{{cite news |first=Clare |last=Hutchinson |work=The Western Mail |date=13 October 2009 |title='Come on, Paxman, if you think you're hard enough...' says wicked Humphrys ; Questions at 20 paces in quiz duel \u2013 and we'll even make it easy for you Humphrys |publisher=Western Mail and Echo Ltd |page=14}}</ref> He appeared again on ''Mastermind'' in 2000, with the animated television show ''[[The Simpsons]]'' as his specialist subject.<ref>{{cite news |first=KAREN |last=PRICE |title=MASTERMIND ACCUSED OF SELLING OUT IN RATINGS FIGHT |work=Western Mail |date=6 August 2004 |page=10 |publisher=Western Mail and Echo Ltd|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/2004/08/06/mastermind-accused-of-selling-out-in-ratings-fight-91466-14502345/2/}}</ref> Also in 2000, he competed on ''[[Countdown (game show)|Countdown]]'', narrowly losing his first game on a crucial conundrum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wiki.apterous.org/Episode_2771|title=Episode 2771 \u2013 Countdown|publisher=}}</ref> In 2001 he appeared on ''[[Stake Out (game show)|Stake Out]]'', where he was the second contestant eliminated during the Face Off round. In 2003, he appeared on ''[[Grand Slam (UK game show)|Grand Slam]]'', where he lost against [[Clive Spate]] in his first match.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com:80/entertainment/tv/microsites/G/grandslam/review_03.html|title=Match Review \u2013 Game 01 \u2013 Channel 4 \u2013 Grand Slam|website=Channel 4|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040831151925/http://www.channel4.com/entertainment/tv/microsites/G/grandslam/review_03.html|archive-date=31 August 2004|url-status=dead|access-date=10 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, he won \u00a3500 on the [[Channel 5 (UK)|Channel 5]] show ''[[BrainTeaser]]'', and a year later he won \u00a31,500 on BBC One's ''[[SUDO-Q]]''.<ref name=\"lucky\" /> In 2005, he won \u00a332,000 on ''Millionaire Live'', a live version of ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' that toured seaside resorts throughout the summer.<ref name=\"lucky\" /><ref>{{cite news |first= John Paul |last=Hedge |title=Winners walk off with two cars and \u00a316k |work=Herald Express |location=Torquay |date=5 September 2005 |publisher=Herald Express (Torquay) |page=4}}</ref> As captain, he led the Welsh quiz team to fifth place in the 2006 [[European Quizzing Championships]].<ref name=\"bbc\"/> \n\nLabbett's team, the Rugby Boys, won [[BBC Four]]'s ''[[Only Connect]]'' in 2009.<ref>{{cite news |title=NEWSBRIEF |work=South Wales Echo |date=1 September 2009 |page=6 |publisher=Western Mail and Echo Ltd}}</ref> Other television appearances include ''[[The National Lottery People's Quiz]]'' (2007) where he came second in the grand final,<ref>{{cite news |first=Olav |last=Bjortomt |authorlink=Olav Bjortomt |title=Your starter for \u00a3200,000 (subscription required) |date=23 June 2007 |work=The Times (The Knowledge) |page=33 |publisher=Times Newspapers Limited |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/tv-radio/article2440448.ece}}</ref> ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?'',<ref name=\"guard1\">{{cite news |first=Stuart |last=Heritage |title=The Chase: how to make the perfect daytime gameshow |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2010/jun/28/the-chase-gameshow-itv |date=28 June 2010 |work=The Guardian |accessdate= 23 June 2012}}</ref> where he won \u00a332,000, ''[[University Challenge]]''<ref name=\"wm\"/> and ''[[Are You an Egghead?]]''.\n\nIn 2012, Labbett was ranked 89th in the [[World Quizzing Championship]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldquizzing.com/results/|title=Results|work=worldquizzing.com|access-date=2 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120607192638/http://www.worldquizzing.com/results/|archive-date=7 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Labbett took part in the three-part [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''[[Sugar Free Farm]]'', when he revealed he has false teeth, as a result of eating too much sugar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/presscentre/ep1week4/sugar-free-farm|title=Sugar Free Farm Episode 1|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tv.bt.com/tv/tv-news/the-chases-mark-labbett-reveals-he-wears-false-teeth-due-to-daily-10-bar-chocolate-habit-11364037330556|title=The Chase's Mark Labbett reveals he wears false teeth due to daily 10 bar chocolate habit|newspaper=BT.com|access-date=19 December 2016}}</ref> That same year, it was announced that he would become a producer for Hull-based wrestling promotion [[New Generation Wrestling]] (NGW).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ngwuk.com/news/Labbett/|title=NGW: 'The Beast' comes to NGW|website=www.ngwuk.com|access-date=2 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n==== ''The Chase'' ====\n{{See also|The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase (U.S. game show)|The Chase Australia}}\nLabbett is one of the \"chasers\" in the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] teatime quiz ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase]]'', first broadcast in 2009 and hosted by [[Bradley Walsh]]. In the show, his nickname is \"The Beast\",<ref name='bristol'>{{cite news|url=http://www.thisissouthwales.co.uk/Quiz-beast-appearance/story-16062113-detail/story.html|title=Quiz beast appearance|date=12 May 2012|work=Bristol Evening Post|page=19|publisher=Bristol United Press}}</ref> a two-pronged nickname referencing both his stature and his surname (Labbett sounds like the French ''la b\u00eate'', meaning \"the beast\").\n\nIn August 2013, Labbett appeared as the only chaser on the [[The Chase (U.S. game show)|U.S. version]] of ''The Chase'' on [[Game Show Network]]. He also appears as one of the seven chasers on the [[The Chase Australia|Australian version]] of ''The Chase'' on the [[Seven Network]], alongside fellow UK chasers [[Anne Hegerty]] and [[Shaun Wallace]].<ref name=\"Australia2016\"/> His weakest subjects are [[horse racing]] and [[soap opera]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RMobd0rLMZc|title=The Chase's Beast Reveals His Quiz Knowledge Achilles Heel \u2013 Lorraine|author=Lorraine|date=23 January 2017|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref> He noted that the American version posed far more difficulties for him, as American game shows typically allow far more competent contestants than British or Australian shows; he stated that his most challenging opponent was [[James Holzhauer]], co-winner of the American version of ''The Chase'' and later a famous ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' contestant.<ref name=holzhauerexplains>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2019/04/james-holzhauer-jeopardy-1-million-win-or-lose/587878/|title=James Holzhauer Explains the Strategy Behind His Jeopardy Winning Streak|last=Pinsker|first=Joe|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=April 24, 2019|accessdate=April 24, 2019|quote=I've got to give ''Jeopardy!'' immense credit, and ''The Chase'' U.S.A. In Britain or Australia, James would not have made it onto television, because he's just too damn good. They would never have him on.}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nLabbett moved to [[Caldicot, Monmouthshire|Caldicot]], [[Monmouthshire]], in 1998 and then to nearby [[Newport, Wales|Newport]] in 2003 before moving to Moorgate, [[Rotherham]], in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/quiz-sensation-successfully-chases-dream-6466365 |title=The Chase quiz sensation Mark 'The Beast' Labbett cracks America |last= Gaskell |first=Simon |date=5 January 2014 |website=[[Wales Online]] |access-date=2 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Chase's Beast moves to South Yorkshire |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/chase-s-beast-moves-to-south-yorkshire-1-5268888 |newspaper=[[Sheffield Star|The Star]] |location=Sheffield, UK |date=2 January 2013 |access-date=2 February 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141028234446/http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/chase-s-beast-moves-to-south-yorkshire-1-5268888 |archive-date=28 October 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He resides in or near [[Herefordshire]].<ref>Philips, Jessica (23 October 2015). [http://www.herefordtimes.com/news/13891554.TV_chaser__the_Beast__visits_Herefordshire_tearoom/ \"TV chaser 'the Beast' visits Herefordshire tearoom\"]. ''[[Hereford Times]]''.</ref> He is [[Type-II diabetic]].<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/866050/The-Chase-Mark-Labbett-life-changing-Type-2-diabetes-diagnosis-weight-loss-diet-ITV|title=The Chase star Mark Labbett reveals life-changing diagnosis: 'No arguments now'| last= Wright|first=Minnie|date=17 October 2017| work=Express.co.uk|access-date= 23 July 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nLabbett married his wife, Katie,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3wJuKZsqUfE|title=The Chase's Beast Introduces His Wife Katie |publisher= Loose Women|date=21 August 2017 |via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> who is his second cousin and 27 years his junior, in October 2014 at [[Arundel Cathedral]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Yaqoob |first=Janine |date=11 October 2014 |title=The Chase game show star Mark 'Beast' Labbett marries girl less than half his age |url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/chase-star-mark-beast-labbett-4421923 |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |location=London |access-date=2 February 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Winter 2014 Edition |url= http://www.arundelcathedral.org/proclaimer/Proclaimer_Winter_2014.pdf |work= Parish Proclaimer |location=Arundel |date=2014 |access-date=2 February 2016}}</ref> They have a son.<ref>https://www.ok.co.uk/tv/chase-mark-labbett-weight-loss-14359370.amp</ref> The couple reportedly separated in 2019<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.express.co.uk/celebrity-news/1126035/mark-labbett-wife-katie-marriage-split-cheating-the-chase-itv-latest-news-updates|title=Mark Labbett: The Chase star\u2019s wife Katie breaks silence on their SPLIT 'It's hard'|work=Daily Express|date=12 May 2019|accessdate=27 May 2019| first= Michelle|last=Marshall}}</ref> but reconciled for the sake of their child.<ref>{{Cite web| url= https://metro.co.uk/2019/09/10/chase-star-mark-labbett-confirms-wife-katie-still-together-priority-son-10717301/| title=The Chase star Mark Labbett and wife Katie are back together |last= Deen|first=Sarah|access-date=2019-11-03}}</ref>\n\nLabbett's favourite [[association football|football]] team is [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sheffieldtelegraph.co.uk/news/mark-labbett-talked-the-chase-co-star-anne-hegerty-into-im-a-celebrity-get-me-out-of-here-206709 |title= Mark Labbett 'talked' The Chase co-star Anne Hegerty into I'm A Celebrity Get Me Out Of Here| work= Sheffield Telegraph| access-date=2019-11-03|language=en-GB| issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\n== Television ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Channel\n|-\n| 2009\u2014\n| ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase]]''\n| rowspan=\"5\" |Chaser\n|[[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n|-\n| 2011\u2014\n| ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Chase: Celebrity Specials]]''\n|rowspan |ITV\n|-\n| 2013\u20132015\n| ''[[The Chase (U.S. game show)|The Chase USA]]''\n| [[Game Show Network]]\n|-\n| 2016\u2014\n| ''[[The Chase Australia]]''\n| [[Seven Network|Channel 7]]\n|-\n| 2017\u2014\n| ''[[The Chase (UK game show)|The Family Chase]]''\n|rowspan | ITV\n|}\n\n=== Guest appearances ===\n*''[[Mastermind (TV series)|Mastermind]]'' (1999, 2000) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Countdown (game show)|Countdown]]'' (2000) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Stake Out (game show)|Stake Out]]'' (2001) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Grand Slam (UK game show)|Grand Slam]]'' (2003) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[BrainTeaser]]'' (2004) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[SUDO-Q]]'' (2005) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[University Challenge]]'' \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (UK game show)|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' (2006) \u2013 contestant<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/mark-labbett-beast-the-chase-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-video_uk_586f83d8e4b0961f0937b27e|title=\u2018The Chase\u2019 Star Mark Labbett Was On \u2018Who Wants To Be A Millionaire\u2019 (But How Much Did He Win?)|date=6 January 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n*''[[The National Lottery People's Quiz]]'' (2007) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Are You an Egghead?]]'' (2008) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Only Connect]]'' (2009) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Sugar Free Farm]]'' (2016) \u2013 participant\n*''[[Tipping Point (game show)|Tipping Point: Lucky Stars]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.digitalspy.com/tv/news/a813061/the-chase-tipping-point-charity-special/|title=The Chase and Tipping Point are crossing over!|date=3 November 2016|publisher=}}</ref> (2016) \u2013 contestant\n*''[[Let's Sing and Dance|Let's Sing and Dance for Comic Relief]]'' (2017) \u2013 participant\n*''[[Celebrity Juice]]'' (2017) \u2013 participant\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links == \n{{Portal|Biography|Television}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=3584757|name=Mark Labbett}}\n*{{Official website|http://www.marklabbett.co.uk/}}\n\n{{The Chase}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Labbett, Mark}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:People from Tiverton, Devon]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Exeter]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Exeter College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glamorgan]]\n[[Category:English television personalities]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Contestants on British game shows]]\n[[Category:Contestants on University Challenge]]\n", "name_user": "WahPow", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated to include radio 1 do appearance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Labbett"}
{"title_page": "Jabal al-Bilas", "text_new": "'''Jabal al-Bilas''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0628\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0633}}) is a desert height located 500 meters (1,640 ft) above sea level in [[Syria]].<ref name=\"Al-Fares\">{{harvnb|Al-Fares|2013|p=47}}</ref>\n\nA marker, laid by Roman governor [[Quintus Caecilius Metellus Creticus Silanus|Silanus]] 75 kilometres (47 mi) northwest of [[Palmyra]], was found there, probably marking the Palmyrene's boundaries with [[Hama|Epiphania]].<ref>{{harvnb|Seyrig|1959|p=190}}</ref>\n\nOccasional old pistachio trees of up to 5 meters in height can still be found there.<ref name=\"Al-Fares\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite book|last=Al-Fares|first=Wafi|title=Historical Land Use/Land Cover Classification Using Remote Sensing: A Case Study of the Euphrates River Basin in Syria|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2iGzGgPxzPQC|year=2013|publisher=Springer|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Seyrig|first=Henri|authorlink=Henri Seyrig|date=1959|title=Antiquit\u00e9s Syriennes 76: Caract\u00e8res de l'histoire d'\u00c9m\u00e8se|journal=[[Syria (journal)|Syria]]|volume=36|issue=3\u20134|url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/syria_0039-7946_1959_num_36_3_5394|lang=fr|ref=harv}} {{free access}}\n\n{{coord missing|Syria}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Syria]]\n\n\n{{Syria-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Jabal al-Bilas''' ({{lang-ar|\u062c\u0628\u0644 \u0627\u0644\u0628\u0644\u0639\u0627\u0633}}) is a desert height located 500 meters (1,640 ft) above sea level in [[Syria]].<ref name=\"Al-Fares\">{{harvnb|Al-Fares|2013|p=47}}</ref>\n\nA marker, laid by Roman governor [[Quintus Caecilius Metellus Creticus Silanus|Silanus]] 75 kilometres (47 mi) northwest of [[Palmyra]], was found there, probably marking the Palmyrene's boundaries with [[Hama|Epiphania]].<ref>{{harvnb|Seyrig|1959|p=190}}</ref>\n\nOccasional old pistachio trees of up to 5 meters in height can still be found there.<ref name=\"Al-Fares\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* {{Cite book|last=Al-Fares|first=Wafi|title=Historical Land Use/Land Cover Classification Using Remote Sensing: A Case Study of the Euphrates River Basin in Syria|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2iGzGgPxzPQC|year=2013|publisher=Springer|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite journal|last=Seyrig|first=Henri|authorlink=Henri Seyrig|date=1959|title=Antiquit\u00e9s Syriennes 76: Caract\u00e8res de l'histoire d'\u00c9m\u00e8se|journal=[[Syria (journal)|Syria]]|volume=36|issue=3\u20134|url=https://www.persee.fr/doc/syria_0039-7946_1959_num_36_3_5394|lang=fr|ref=harv}} {{free access}}\n\n{{coord missing|Syria}}\n\n[[Category:Mountains of Syria]]\n\n{{stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jmertel23", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2013{{Stub}}, +{{Syria-geo-stub}} usingStubSorter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jabal_al-Bilas"}
{"title_page": "Worms (1995 video game)", "text_new": "{{About||the 2007 game|Worms (2007 video game)|the 1983 game|Worms?}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{under construction|placedby=KGRAMR|nosection=yes}}\n{{in use}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title        = Worms\n| image        = Worms-win-cover.jpg\n| image_size   = 256px\n| caption      = \n| developer    = [[Team17]]\n| publisher    = [[Ocean Software]]\n| designer     = [[Andy Davidson (game designer)|Andy Davidson]]\n|composer      = [[Bj\u00f8rn Lynne]]\n| series       = ''[[Worms (series)|Worms]]''\n| engine       = \n| released     = '''Amiga, CD32, Game Boy & Mac'''<br />{{vgrelease|EU|1995<ref>{{MobyGames|id=/worms|name=''Worms''}}</ref><ref>[http://amr.abime.net/review_10209 Worms review from CU Amiga Magazine (Dec 1995) \u2013 Amiga Magazine Rack] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220093731/http://amr.abime.net/review_10209 |date=2012-02-20 }}</ref>}}'''Mega Drive'''<br />{{vgrelease|EU|June 1, 1995}}'''PC (DOS)'''<br />{{Video game release|NA|October 31, 1995 (Retail)|EU|1995|NA|October 19, 2011 (Steam)}}'''PlayStation'''<br />{{Video game release|NA|1996|EU|November, 1995<ref name=\"CTW565\">{{cite magazine |title=Christmas Games Guide |magazine=Computer Trade Weekly |location=United Kingdom |date=27 November 1995 |issue=565 |page=43 }}</ref>|JP|February 28, 1997}}'''SNES'''<br />{{vgrelease|EU|September 29, 1996}}'''Saturn'''<br />{{Video game release|NA|1996|EU|1995|JP|March 14, 1997}}'''Jaguar'''<br />{{vgrelease|NA|May 15, 1998}}\n| genre        = [[Artillery game|Artillery]], [[Strategy video game|Strategy]]\n| modes        = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n| platforms    = [[Amiga]], [[Amiga CD32]], [[Game Boy]], [[Sega Genesis]], [[Atari Jaguar]], [[Mac OS]], [[IBM PC compatible]] ([[MS-DOS]]), [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]], [[Sega Saturn]], [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|Super NES]]\n}}\n'''''Worms''''' is a 2D [[Artillery game|artillery]] [[Strategy video game|tactical]] video game developed by [[Team17]] and released in [[1995 in video gaming|1995]]. It is the first game in the [[Worms (series)|''Worms series'']] of video games.\n\n''Worms'' is a [[turn based]] game where a player controls a team of worms against other teams of worms that are controlled by a computer or human opponent. The aim is to use various weapons to kill the worms on the other teams and have the last surviving worm(s).\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[Image:Worms scrapyardscreenshot.png|thumb|left|From the [[Amiga]] version: A [[scrapyard]] themed level, with the player using the [[blowtorch]] tool.]]\n''Worms'' is a turn based [[artillery game]], similar to other early games in the genre such as ''[[Scorched Earth (video game)|Scorched Earth]].\nEach player controls a team of several worms. During the course of the game, players take turns selecting one of their worms. They then use whatever tools and weapons are available to attack and kill the opponents' worms, thereby winning the game. Worms may move around the terrain in a variety of ways, normally by walking and jumping but also by using particular tools such as the \"Bungee\" and \"Ninja Rope\", to move to otherwise inaccessible areas. Each turn is time-limited to ensure that players do not hold up the game with excessive thinking or moving. The time limit can be modified in some of the games in the Worms series.\n\nOver fifty weapons and tools may be available each time a game is played, and differing selections of weapons and tools can be saved into a \"scheme\" for easy selection in future games. Other scheme settings allow options such as deployment of reinforcement crates, from which additional weapons can be obtained, and sudden death where the game is rushed to a conclusion after a time limit expires. Some settings provide for the inclusion of objects such as land mines and explosive barrels.\n\nWhen most weapons are used, they cause explosions that deform the terrain, creating circular cavities. If a worm is hit with a weapon, they will lose health. A worm who is out of health will die by blowing themselves up and leaving a grave marker. Worms can also die by being thrown off the side of the map or by falling into the water at the map's base.\n\n== Development ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThe game was originally created by Andy Davidson as an entry for a [[Blitz BASIC]] programming competition run by the ''[[Amiga Format]]'' magazine, a cut-down version of the [[programming language]] having been covermounted previously. The game at this stage was called '''''Total Wormage''''' (possibly in reference to ''[[Total Carnage]]'') and it did not win the competition. Davidson sent the game to several publishers with no success. He then took the game to the [[European Computer Trade Show]], where he met with Mark Foreman \u2013 Head Games Buyer at GEM Distribution. Mark suggested to Andy that he should speak to Ocean/Team17 as they would be an ideal partner \u2013 they also had a stand at the show. Team17 made an offer on-the-spot to develop and publish the game.<ref>IGN [ Worms Blast Preview]</ref><ref>GameSpy [ Worms: Open Warfare Developer Diary]</ref>\n\nThe references to the developers' home county, [[Yorkshire]], is visible, with a soundbank named \"Tykes\", which is a Yorkshire accent, and in the \"Hell\" level found in the single player mission mode, a sign with \"Welcome to [[Ossett]]! Ha! ha! ha!\" written on it.\n===Character, level and sound design===\nThe game's graphics and sound design is primarily 'cartoon-like' (though less so than the later games in the series). Levels designs are randomly generated by the use of alpha-numeric strings as their [[Random seed|seeds]]. The object and landscape sets used to generate the field are arranged into 'themes' including forests, martian landscapes, beaches and 'hell'.\n\n== Release ==\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nThe North American release of the [[PlayStation (console)|PlayStation]] version was the subject of considerable negotiation, as Sony Computer Entertainment of America had a policy against 2D games being published for the console.<ref name=\"NGenPSw\"/> The [[Sega Saturn]] version of the game was a straight port of the PlayStation version.<ref name=\"SSMukSSw\"/>\n\nAn [[Atari Jaguar]] version was also developed by Team17 and published by [[Telegames]] in May 15, 1998.<ref>{{cite magazine|last=Charlton|first=Frank|url=http://www.stformat.com/stf85/pages_nx1500/stf85_010.jpg|title=STF News... - Worms wriggles in|magazine=[[ST Format]]|issue=85|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=August 1996|page=10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Jason|url=http://www.jaguarsector.com/index.php?autocom=ibwiki&cmd=article&do=print_article&id=379|title=Atari Jaguar Timeline|website=jaguarsector.com|accessdate=2018-09-13|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130629025431/http://www.jaguarsector.com/index.php?autocom=ibwiki&cmd=article&do=print_article&id=379|archivedate=29 June 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> Telegames announced the release of this version after becoming the last remaining software publisher for the Jaguar and like other games published following the system's discontinuation,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File%3AEGM_US_094.pdf&page=24|title=Tidbits...|magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=94|publisher=[[Ziff Davis]]|date=May 1997|page=24}}</ref> ''Worms'' could be purchased either through [[Direct selling|direct order]] from Telegames' US and UK websites or select retailers such as [[EB Games|Electronics Boutique]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last=|first=|url=https://retrocdn.net/index.php?title=File:GamePro_US_105.pdf&page=22|title=News Bits|magazine=[[GamePro]]|issue=105|publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG]]|date=June 1997|page=20}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/stream/Gamefan_Vol_5_Issue_10#page/n41|title=Recent Sightings of an Endangered Species|magazine=[[GameFan]]|volume=5|issue=10|publisher=Shinno Media|date=October 1997|page=36}}</ref> It also served as the final title released for the console to be officially licensed with the Atari name, as the rights to said name and other [[intellectual property]] rights of [[Atari Corporation]] were sold to [[Hasbro Interactive]] before [[JT Storage]]'s bankruptcy in [[1999 in video gaming|1999]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.host.fptoday.com/melek/jaguar/jag-96.htm|title=Hasbro Interactive Acquires Legendary Atari Game Property Assets|website=Nine Lives|date=March 16, 1998|accessdate=2018-12-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051107232949/http://www.host.fptoday.com/melek/jaguar/jag-96.htm|archivedate=7 November 2005|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n=== Cancelled ports ===\nIn 1995, Team17 began development on a port of ''Worms'' to [[Nintendo]]'s [[Virtual Boy]] platform.<ref name=\"MMan\u00edav3i8\">{{cite magazine|author=|url=https://archive.org/stream/MicromaniaTerceraEpocaSpanishIssue8#page/n57/mode/1up|title=Reportaje: Extra\u00f1a mezcla... de gusanos - Worms|magazine=[[Microman\u00eda]]|volume=3|issue=8|publisher=HobbyPress|date=September 1995|page=58|lang=es}}</ref> The game was to be published by Ocean, but was canceled only weeks into development as a result of Nintendo's discontinuation of the console.<ref>{{cite web|last=Radke|first=Christian|url=https://www.planetvb.com/modules/games/?u030g|title=Worms|website=planetvb.com|date=2020|access-date=2020-04-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529195248/https://www.planetvb.com/modules/games/?u030g|archive-date=2019-05-29|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[32X]] release was also planned but never released as well.<ref name=\"MMan\u00edav3i8\"/>\n\n=== Expansion pack ===\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n''Worms Reinforcements'' ([[1996 in video gaming|1996]]) is an expansion pack for ''Worms'', which was later amalgamated with the original game to create ''Worms and Reinforcements United'' (a.k.a. ''Worms United'' or ''Worms Utd.'') the same year. Released only for the [[personal computer|PC]], it added a single player campaign and the ability to add custom levels and soundpacks (which was already available for the [[Amiga]] version). It also included an introductory FMV.\n\n=== Director's cut ===\n{{seealso|Worms: The Director's Cut}}\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n''Worms: The Director's Cut'' ([[1997 in video gaming|1997]]) is a sequel to ''Worms'', available only on the Amiga. It is largely built upon the original Amiga game engine with various gameplay enhancement and additions, as well as graphical improvements and fixes. During the development of ''Worms 2'', Andy Davidson wrote this special edition produced exclusively for the AGA chipset Amiga. Only 5000 copies were ever sold. It was also the last version released for the Commodore Amiga platform from which the game originated.\n\n=== Remake ===\n{{seealso|Worms (2007 video game)}}\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\nA [[Video game remake|remake]], also called ''[[Worms (2007 video game)|Worms]]'', for the Xbox 360 was released in 2007. It has since been released to the PS3, in April 2009, and on the [[iPhone]] on July 11, 2009.\n\n== Reception ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"float:right; font-size:80%; text-align:center; margin:1em; margin-top:0; padding:0; background:none;\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n! colspan=10 style=\"font-size: 100%\" | Reception\n|-\n! colspan=10 | Aggregate scores\n|-\n! rowspan=2  | Aggregator\n! colspan=10 | Scores\n|-\n! [[Amiga]]\n! [[Amiga CD32|CD32]]\n! [[Sega Mega Drive|SMD]]\n! [[Personal computer|PC]]\n! [[PlayStation (console)|PS]]\n! [[Sega Saturn|SS]]\n! [[Game Boy|GB]]\n! [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]]\n! [[Atari Jaguar|Jaguar]]\n|-\n| ''[[GameRankings]]''\n| {{N/A}}\n| {{N/A}}\n| 40%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/926446-worms/index.html|title=Worms for Genesis|work=[[GameRankings]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|date=2019|access-date=2020-04-15|archive-url